1
00:03:10,568 --> 00:03:13,799
Today's review will be the final
operation of training period two.

2
00:03:13,968 --> 00:03:16,177
Instructions for period three
will be issued tomorrow.

3
00:03:16,328 --> 00:03:20,765
Study them. Make your plans.
Stand by for flight quarters.

4
00:03:29,768 --> 00:03:32,965
- First Division ready for flight.
- Second Division ready for flight.

5
00:03:33,128 --> 00:03:36,883
You boys are getting so efficient
you scare me. Come on, they're waiting.

6
00:03:37,088 --> 00:03:40,080
- What course did you get to steer on?
- Course 273 for 15 minutes.

7
00:03:40,248 --> 00:03:43,479
- That's about what I got.
- From this point, we can circle...

8
00:03:45,088 --> 00:03:48,524
Hey. Sit down. I can't see the board.

9
00:03:51,288 --> 00:03:53,564
Bombing pilots, attention.

10
00:03:54,208 --> 00:03:56,040
Rendezvous over the carrier
at 2000 feet.

11
00:03:56,208 --> 00:03:59,121
Gold braid's on the field ashore.
Fly past in mass formation.

12
00:03:59,288 --> 00:04:03,122
Then make a dive-bombing attack.
And don't forget to take your shore legs.

13
00:04:03,288 --> 00:04:05,598
Honolulu. Here we come!

14
00:04:05,768 --> 00:04:09,045
All right. All right. Relax and stand by.
You bunch of ground lovers.

15
00:04:09,208 --> 00:04:11,848
- Taking care of my gear. Tom?
- We'll move it ashore.

16
00:04:12,008 --> 00:04:14,887
- Thanks. - Not at all. I'll
be glad to get rid of you.

17
00:04:15,368 --> 00:04:18,201
- Oh. Have you got a cigarette?
- Yeah.

18
00:04:18,728 --> 00:04:22,084
- Say. What is this? Gold?
- Sure. We've got a friend at Fort Knox.

19
00:04:22,248 --> 00:04:25,366
- You guys didn't buy these on Navy pay.
- We found them under a rock.

20
00:04:25,528 --> 00:04:28,725
You ought to wear specs to go
with them. Or carry a cane.

21
00:04:28,888 --> 00:04:30,481
These certainly make an impression.

22
00:04:30,688 --> 00:04:33,362
Only thing I own that'd make
me welcome in a pawnshop.

23
00:04:33,568 --> 00:04:35,366
They sent them
because Joe rumbled...

24
00:04:35,528 --> 00:04:39,237
- ...with a governor's wife in Cleveland.
- That probably had a lot to do with it.

25
00:04:39,408 --> 00:04:43,163
With the boys running National Air Races.
Thought we'd do better stunts.

26
00:04:43,888 --> 00:04:46,767
Things will be awful tough on Joe
if black cats sprout wings.

27
00:04:46,928 --> 00:04:49,966
National Air Races, five times a day
scraping noses on the ground.

28
00:04:50,128 --> 00:04:51,482
It was worth 18 karats.

29
00:04:51,648 --> 00:04:54,527
Oh. Yeah. But I got the
best deal out of Cleveland.

30
00:04:54,688 --> 00:04:57,328
- 5 feet 2, blue eyes.
- There he goes again.

31
00:04:57,488 --> 00:05:01,004
- Wait till he's washed a million didies.
- And walked with junior's gas pains.

32
00:05:01,168 --> 00:05:02,966
He'll wish he'd taken a cigarette case.

33
00:05:03,168 --> 00:05:06,877
Swede. How'd you get glamor dust in
your eyes? Pilot's a fool to take a wife.

34
00:05:07,088 --> 00:05:10,319
Hazel's broad-minded. She's letting
me off once a week after marriage.

35
00:05:10,528 --> 00:05:12,758
Well. That's better than
being in a penitentiary.

36
00:05:12,928 --> 00:05:17,161
I wish you transferred to San Diego with
us instead of here. After the honeymoon.

37
00:05:17,328 --> 00:05:19,888
Yeah. It's a crime to break
up the three top hats.

38
00:05:20,048 --> 00:05:22,005
Did a lot of loops together
here and there.

39
00:05:22,168 --> 00:05:24,887
Boy. You're gonna miss those times.
So are we.

40
00:05:25,048 --> 00:05:28,564
I'll have a bride to take care of.
You guys will be playing tag with cadets.

41
00:05:28,728 --> 00:05:30,321
I'll play tag-

42
00:05:30,648 --> 00:05:33,481
Pilots. Man your planes.
Pilots. Man your planes.

43
00:05:41,488 --> 00:05:43,684
Stand by to start engines.

44
00:05:46,208 --> 00:05:48,563
Stand clear of Propellers.

45
00:06:55,024 --> 00:06:57,743
She's sweet as sugar, commander.

46
00:07:26,368 --> 00:07:29,406
Doctor. There's something
sort of morbid about our jobs.

47
00:07:29,568 --> 00:07:33,243
Here we sit, day after day.
Like buzzards on a rail fence.

48
00:07:33,408 --> 00:07:35,285
Yeah. I guess you're right. Lucky.

49
00:07:35,448 --> 00:07:38,679
We sort of symbolize the uncertainty
of life for those pilots.

50
00:07:38,848 --> 00:07:42,443
- No wonder they don't love us.
- Oh. I don't mind them. Sir. It's my wife.

51
00:07:42,608 --> 00:07:45,122
She says I have to stop
smelling of iodoform.

52
00:07:45,288 --> 00:07:46,881
Did you ever have complaints on it?

53
00:07:47,048 --> 00:07:50,086
Did I? Only about eight years.
Harvard. Hopkins. Cambridge.

54
00:07:50,288 --> 00:07:52,564
The girls all used to call me
“The Iodoform Kid.“

55
00:07:52,728 --> 00:07:56,437
- Generally. They called me. "Stinky.“"
- How did you manage to get rid of it?

56
00:07:56,608 --> 00:07:58,201
I didn't. They just got used to it.

57
00:07:58,368 --> 00:08:00,518
Killed a lot of romances for me. Lucky.

58
00:08:00,688 --> 00:08:03,567
I should have been smart like you.
Lieutenant, stayed single.

59
00:08:03,728 --> 00:08:06,288
Especially if I'd known
I was coming to Honolulu.

60
00:08:06,448 --> 00:08:09,008
Why. That's fine talk
when you're a new bridegroom.

61
00:08:09,168 --> 00:08:11,398
Three weeks and I got marriage
up to here.

62
00:08:11,568 --> 00:08:12,922
Yeah?

63
00:08:13,088 --> 00:08:16,001
Three more and you'll have it
up to here.

64
00:08:49,448 --> 00:08:51,644
Those planes do something to you.
Don't they?

65
00:09:28,408 --> 00:09:31,526
Almost as good as the Army.

66
00:09:37,368 --> 00:09:38,688
Look at that formation.

67
00:11:53,464 --> 00:11:57,423
Bombing six. Stand by to peel off.

68
00:12:36,728 --> 00:12:39,686
- It's Swede.
- Blackout again.

69
00:13:16,928 --> 00:13:20,284
- You got a cigarette?
- Sure.

70
00:13:20,848 --> 00:13:25,797
I can't move. I can't feel anything.

71
00:13:26,328 --> 00:13:27,727
How did I get"?

72
00:13:33,648 --> 00:13:35,446
Here.

73
00:13:42,488 --> 00:13:44,843
That's good.

74
00:13:46,048 --> 00:13:49,040
What happened, chum?
Did you misjudge your altitude?

75
00:13:49,488 --> 00:13:51,445
It was a dive.

76
00:13:51,608 --> 00:13:54,600
I couldn't pull up.

77
00:13:55,288 --> 00:13:57,438
Blacked out.

78
00:13:59,288 --> 00:14:03,202
Why don't you doctors
do something about that.

79
00:14:04,888 --> 00:14:07,357
Yeah. Why don't we. Here.

80
00:14:08,368 --> 00:14:11,440
Here's the pressure
on the spine right here.

81
00:14:11,848 --> 00:14:14,567
That can only be relieved
by an immediate operation.

82
00:14:14,728 --> 00:14:17,322
Well. He's pretty weak
from shock and loss of blood.

83
00:14:17,488 --> 00:14:20,002
There's a chance if we wait for him
to regain strength.

84
00:14:20,168 --> 00:14:25,561
Wait? Of course. It's your responsibility.
But did a case ever improve by waiting?

85
00:14:25,728 --> 00:14:30,120
He'll never regain consciousness unless
we go in now. I wish I wasn't so certain.

86
00:14:33,648 --> 00:14:36,367
- Who's caring for Larson?
- Commander Martin. Lieutenant Lee.

87
00:14:36,888 --> 00:14:40,358
- You saw him. He's still alive?
- He was. Yes. Sir.

88
00:14:48,488 --> 00:14:50,445
I'm Larson's squadron commander.
How is he?

89
00:14:50,608 --> 00:14:52,519
A concussion. Possibly skull fracture.

90
00:14:52,688 --> 00:14:56,807
Also. The x-rays showed a dislocated
vertebra pressing on the spinal cord here.

91
00:14:56,968 --> 00:14:59,198
It's a problem of whether
to operate now or wait.

92
00:14:59,368 --> 00:15:02,087
I don't wanna be insistent.
But we're wasting valuable time.

93
00:15:02,248 --> 00:15:04,888
- What'll you do for him?
- Does he have family in Honolulu?

94
00:15:05,048 --> 00:15:06,322
- No.
- We're his friends.

95
00:15:06,488 --> 00:15:08,126
We haven't time to worry about that.

96
00:15:08,488 --> 00:15:12,004
Allison's just published a complete
record of over 300 cases of cord injury.

97
00:15:12,168 --> 00:15:14,557
Each single case that recovered
was operated at once.

98
00:15:14,728 --> 00:15:17,770
Every minute the pressure was unrelieved
lessened the chances of recovery.

99
00:15:17,928 --> 00:15:21,683
- What more can I say?
- Perhaps you're right. Come along.

100
00:15:27,688 --> 00:15:29,918
Sponge. Sponge.

101
00:15:33,208 --> 00:15:34,482
Scalpel.

102
00:15:42,048 --> 00:15:43,800
Retractor.

103
00:15:44,568 --> 00:15:47,560
Breathing has stopped.
Pulse is getting very weak.

104
00:16:30,808 --> 00:16:34,005
- Sticky. Isn't it?
- Yeah.

105
00:16:39,848 --> 00:16:41,805
That much injury.
There never was a chance.

106
00:16:41,968 --> 00:16:44,608
No. None whatever.

107
00:17:03,648 --> 00:17:08,677
I'm sorry. But your friend
just died on the table.

108
00:17:09,568 --> 00:17:12,003
Accident cases are always uncertain.

109
00:17:12,168 --> 00:17:16,719
You can never be quite sure of
the extent of shock or internal injuries.

110
00:17:18,208 --> 00:17:20,848
Well. I'm sorry.

111
00:17:26,288 --> 00:17:28,245
You were certain enough a while ago.

112
00:17:28,408 --> 00:17:31,685
Maybe it would have been better to wait.
As the commander said.

113
00:17:31,848 --> 00:17:35,523
No. It wouldn't have made
any difference.

114
00:17:35,688 --> 00:17:38,965
His spinal cord was
almost completely severed.

115
00:17:39,128 --> 00:17:41,563
He said he lost consciousness
pulling out of the dive.

116
00:17:41,728 --> 00:17:43,082
We think he lost it in there.

117
00:17:45,928 --> 00:17:48,124
Everything was done
that could have been done.

118
00:17:48,288 --> 00:17:52,077
I appreciate your feelings. But not your
criticism. It has no sound medical basis.

119
00:17:52,728 --> 00:17:54,765
Are you an example
of sound medical basis?

120
00:18:12,928 --> 00:18:14,601
I sent Hazel a cable and a letter.

121
00:18:14,768 --> 00:18:17,237
She'll be going through
the ringer for a while.

122
00:18:17,528 --> 00:18:19,201
Do you think we ought to see her?

123
00:18:19,368 --> 00:18:21,518
No. It would just get her
all stirred up again.

124
00:18:30,768 --> 00:18:33,328
- Linda!
- Doug.

125
00:18:33,488 --> 00:18:35,798
Pal! What are you doing here
in Honolulu?

126
00:18:35,968 --> 00:18:37,959
Of all the nice people.
How nice to see you.

127
00:18:38,128 --> 00:18:40,722
- It's good to see you too.
- Gosh. You look wonderful.

128
00:18:40,888 --> 00:18:42,799
- Thanks.
- Listen...

129
00:18:43,568 --> 00:18:45,559
Come over here.
I want to talk to you.

130
00:18:45,728 --> 00:18:48,117
How many times have I told you
to stop following me?

131
00:18:48,768 --> 00:18:50,406
Who said I was following you around?

132
00:18:50,568 --> 00:18:52,878
I'm with friends and got bored
and went for a walk.

133
00:18:53,328 --> 00:18:55,444
Of course. I was hoping I might run...

134
00:18:56,368 --> 00:18:59,645
Okay. I'm following you around.

135
00:18:59,808 --> 00:19:01,242
But in a very refined way.

136
00:19:01,888 --> 00:19:05,119
Darling. Why do you waste your time
on me? You're much too nice for me.

137
00:19:05,288 --> 00:19:07,165
- Am I?
- Sure. You are.

138
00:19:07,328 --> 00:19:10,525
I've told you, as far as I'm concerned.
A woman is like an elephant.

139
00:19:10,688 --> 00:19:13,567
I like to look at them.
But I don't want to own one. Come on.

140
00:19:16,248 --> 00:19:20,162
- Hey. Peter. A table for two.
- Over there.

141
00:19:23,128 --> 00:19:25,927
Now. Two of those tall green horrors
of yours.

142
00:19:26,088 --> 00:19:27,487
That will kill us or cure us.

143
00:19:28,048 --> 00:19:30,767
You're a double-dyed. No-good.
Cold-hearted wretch. Douglas.

144
00:19:32,328 --> 00:19:34,763
Somehow. I find you very entertaining.

145
00:19:34,928 --> 00:19:36,919
What? Oh. Thanks.

146
00:19:37,088 --> 00:19:40,718
Well. How is good old Jack
back there in Washington?

147
00:19:40,968 --> 00:19:43,164
His name is Charlie.
And he lives in Baltimore.

148
00:19:43,328 --> 00:19:48,118
Yeah. Old Charlie. That's what I said.
Well. How is he? Swell guy.

149
00:19:48,288 --> 00:19:50,359
I always used to get so jealous of him.

150
00:19:50,528 --> 00:19:55,045
Shall I phone and tell him I've caught the
mumps or something and stay a while?

151
00:19:57,168 --> 00:19:58,488
Yeah. Sure. Do that.

152
00:19:58,928 --> 00:20:02,046
Did you hear what I said?
I'm offering to stay another week.

153
00:20:02,208 --> 00:20:05,041
What? Oh. Another week.
Why. Darling. That will be wonderful.

154
00:20:05,208 --> 00:20:08,087
I hope you can make it.
Look. Will you excuse me just a moment?

155
00:20:08,248 --> 00:20:09,602
I must talk to these fellas.

156
00:20:09,768 --> 00:20:12,681
Why do I keep tossing myself at you?
Why am I such a chump?

157
00:20:12,848 --> 00:20:16,239
Darling. You're not a chump.
I'll be right back.

158
00:20:19,408 --> 00:20:22,526
Say. Could I buy you fellas a drink?

159
00:20:23,208 --> 00:20:24,960
No. Thanks.

160
00:20:27,528 --> 00:20:31,123
I just... Oh, thanks, I'll have it here.

161
00:20:32,608 --> 00:20:36,317
I just wanted to tell you I'm sorry
for sounding off that way this morning.

162
00:20:36,488 --> 00:20:38,399
I guess we're all wound up
a bit too tight.

163
00:20:38,568 --> 00:20:39,967
Yeah.

164
00:20:41,688 --> 00:20:47,047
You know. This blackout in dive-bombing
is a very interesting medical subject.

165
00:20:47,208 --> 00:20:48,528
I just read a report on it.

166
00:20:48,688 --> 00:20:52,044
Seems those German Stuka pilots
have been hit hard.

167
00:20:52,328 --> 00:20:54,239
You find a way to make
pullouts easier?

168
00:20:54,448 --> 00:20:58,043
Sure. Cut down your diving speed with
flaps and just hang up there in the air.

169
00:20:58,208 --> 00:21:00,597
Then you're a pushover
for antiaircraft fire.

170
00:21:00,768 --> 00:21:02,088
Yeah. It's tough. All right.

171
00:21:02,248 --> 00:21:05,286
But I still think with proper research.
We'll lick those problems.

172
00:21:05,448 --> 00:21:09,237
It's a cinch. The new German bombers
are coming in at about 38,000 feet.

173
00:21:09,408 --> 00:21:13,003
All RAF fighters have to do is top
that by a few thousand feet to attack.

174
00:21:13,168 --> 00:21:15,603
Trouble is. When you're that high.
You're unconscious.

175
00:21:15,768 --> 00:21:17,964
Say. That brings up
another interesting problem.

176
00:21:18,128 --> 00:21:21,962
Dr. Collins has new work on high-altitude
sickness. What's it doing to your outfit?

177
00:21:22,608 --> 00:21:24,963
Three men in the sickbay.
And one funeral.

178
00:21:25,128 --> 00:21:28,120
We don't know whether that last one
was high-altitude sickness...

179
00:21:28,288 --> 00:21:30,484
blackout or just too much
smart surgery.

180
00:21:34,088 --> 00:21:36,967
It must be pretty uncomfortable
up at 30.000 feet. Isn't it?

181
00:21:37,168 --> 00:21:38,761
Not at all. Doc. It's great sport.

182
00:21:38,928 --> 00:21:41,602
Freeze. Get nutty from no oxygen.
Crash. Break your neck.

183
00:21:41,768 --> 00:21:43,167
You ought to try it some time.

184
00:21:44,568 --> 00:21:48,163
Thanks. Well, just thought we might
learn something from each other.

185
00:21:48,328 --> 00:21:49,966
I've learned one thing from you.

186
00:21:50,128 --> 00:21:52,768
If you pill rollers flew more.
You might find how to help.

187
00:21:52,928 --> 00:21:55,397
- I agree with you.
- How many hops you made this week?

188
00:21:55,568 --> 00:21:58,606
Me? None. I'm not a flight surgeon.
Just a routine doctor.

189
00:21:58,808 --> 00:22:01,243
Then keep your amateur flying talk
to yourself. Doc...

190
00:22:01,408 --> 00:22:03,319
till you get your feet off the ground.

191
00:22:03,488 --> 00:22:06,799
Pilots like Swede die because
so-called experts can't keep them alive.

192
00:22:06,968 --> 00:22:11,485
- You don't even fly. And still you got...
- Wait a minute. Listen. I'm on your side.

193
00:22:11,648 --> 00:22:15,084
I agree. Medical science is far too much
in the dark about these things.

194
00:22:15,288 --> 00:22:18,918
Then give the flight surgeons a hand.
Maybe all they need is a genius like you.

195
00:22:19,968 --> 00:22:22,244
Wouldn't it be funny
if that's what they did need?

196
00:22:22,408 --> 00:22:26,117
It'd be more than funny.
It'd be a first-class, full-grown miracle.

197
00:22:26,288 --> 00:22:28,199
Give me a check.

198
00:22:44,128 --> 00:22:46,768
Remember me?
Linda. The girl you met out there.

199
00:22:46,928 --> 00:22:48,760
I'm sorry for staying away so long.

200
00:22:48,928 --> 00:22:51,317
I didn't mean to.
We got on some important subjects.

201
00:22:51,488 --> 00:22:55,561
So I surmised. I also surmise I'm not
one of them. As far as you're concerned.

202
00:22:55,728 --> 00:22:57,446
- Don't be mad.
- Oh. I'm not mad.

203
00:22:57,648 --> 00:23:00,447
I don't mind anything sweet.
That's my chief attraction.

204
00:23:00,608 --> 00:23:03,441
- I know.
- We'll have a date if you can remember.

205
00:23:03,648 --> 00:23:06,322
- Fine.
- And I decided not to stay for a while.

206
00:23:06,488 --> 00:23:08,206
Good night.

207
00:23:11,968 --> 00:23:13,845
Too much sugar in the bloodstream.

208
00:23:59,968 --> 00:24:05,441
Torpedo Squadron 6 from tower.
Wind northwest. Take off when ready.

209
00:24:38,608 --> 00:24:42,317
Thirty years ago. The Navy had
one airplane and two pilots.

210
00:24:42,728 --> 00:24:46,084
Only 20 years ago. A Naval aviator
was the first man to fly the Atlantic.

211
00:24:46,968 --> 00:24:51,121
In those few years. The men who learned
to fly here really built Naval aviation.

212
00:24:51,288 --> 00:24:54,007
And now you're here
to learn to fly and to fight...

213
00:24:54,168 --> 00:24:56,159
become a part of that heritage.

214
00:24:56,328 --> 00:24:58,365
Soon you'll be looking back
and realizing...

215
00:24:58,528 --> 00:25:02,044
that each of you has shared
in making history as it is made today.

216
00:25:02,208 --> 00:25:04,085
All right. March to ground school.

217
00:25:04,288 --> 00:25:06,802
Attention. Left face.

218
00:25:06,968 --> 00:25:09,198
Forward. March.

219
00:25:31,728 --> 00:25:35,437
I know you're trying. Everybody's trying.
In fact. The Navy is famous for trying.

220
00:25:35,608 --> 00:25:39,488
But if small planes make you dizzy.
You'd better go back to Philadelphia.

221
00:25:39,648 --> 00:25:42,288
We won't order another transfer
to teach you to fly.

222
00:25:42,448 --> 00:25:44,041
- Now. You think it over.
- Yes. Sir.

223
00:25:44,208 --> 00:25:47,326
- He's in a bad mood this morning.
- He's in a very good mood for him.

224
00:25:47,488 --> 00:25:50,207
- That's all.
- Yes. Sir.

225
00:25:53,408 --> 00:25:56,799
Any of you guys can't find a room.
I'll share my doghouse with you.

226
00:25:56,968 --> 00:26:00,120
- You're next. Sir.
- Thanks.

227
00:26:00,288 --> 00:26:02,598
- You better stand away from that door.
- Why. Sir?

228
00:26:02,768 --> 00:26:05,442
I don't want you to get hurt
when I get thrown through it.

229
00:26:07,288 --> 00:26:08,562
- Morning. Sir.
- Morning.

230
00:26:08,728 --> 00:26:11,561
Lieutenant Lee, reporting
for flight-surgeon instruction.

231
00:26:11,728 --> 00:26:14,846
- Welcome to San Diego. Doctor.
- Thank you. Sir.

232
00:26:15,008 --> 00:26:16,999
- Bachelor, eh?
- Oh, yes, sir.

233
00:26:17,168 --> 00:26:20,763
Good. Married officers always want
to go home for lunch.

234
00:26:21,768 --> 00:26:25,921
- You did Naval Air Station. Pearl Harbor.
- Right. Sir. Pretty much a wasted year.

235
00:26:26,088 --> 00:26:30,286
But now I've got some ideas for research
on blackout and high-altitude sickness.

236
00:26:30,448 --> 00:26:32,564
Ideas for research are good
to have around.

237
00:26:33,128 --> 00:26:35,483
We've even got a couple here
ourselves. Lieutenant.

238
00:26:36,208 --> 00:26:38,404
Oh. Well. That's very gratifying. Sir.

239
00:26:43,368 --> 00:26:47,043
- Analysis of student rejections.
- Thanks. I'll read it later.

240
00:26:47,208 --> 00:26:51,361
Oh. Lieutenant Commander Rogers.
In charge of research...

241
00:26:52,328 --> 00:26:54,399
Lieutenant Lee.
Student flight surgeon.

242
00:26:54,568 --> 00:26:55,888
- How do you do, sir?
- Hello.

243
00:26:56,048 --> 00:26:58,688
Lee tells me he's got ideas for research
along your line.

244
00:26:58,848 --> 00:27:01,237
- Look after him. Will you?
- Right. Sir.

245
00:27:01,408 --> 00:27:03,240
Come along.

246
00:27:13,288 --> 00:27:15,848
What's your school?
The diploma mill of Hoosier State?

247
00:27:16,008 --> 00:27:17,601
No. Harvard. Hopkins. Cambridge.

248
00:27:17,768 --> 00:27:20,157
- I can read and write.
- Very impressive.

249
00:27:20,328 --> 00:27:23,002
How'd you offer the Navy so much
for so little in return?

250
00:27:23,168 --> 00:27:26,365
- I'm just naturally generous.
- Not to mention your devastating wit.

251
00:27:26,968 --> 00:27:29,278
Now I'd appreciate it
if you'd answer my question.

252
00:27:29,448 --> 00:27:32,167
I joined the Navy because it offered
an active medical life.

253
00:27:32,328 --> 00:27:34,239
Then I got interested
in aviation medicine.

254
00:27:34,408 --> 00:27:37,287
I applied for the flight surgeon's course.
And here I am.

255
00:27:37,448 --> 00:27:41,237
- I trust that meets your approval. Sir?
- Temporarily. It does.

256
00:27:41,448 --> 00:27:43,917
Go to bachelor quarters
and report at 8 a.m. tomorrow.

257
00:27:44,088 --> 00:27:46,443
- When do I start flying?
- Just leave that to us.

258
00:27:46,608 --> 00:27:49,805
- We'll see you get lots of nice
little rides. - Well. Thanks.

259
00:27:49,968 --> 00:27:53,359
And don't think I don't appreciate
the one I've just been having.

260
00:28:19,888 --> 00:28:22,243
Put her down and keep her down.

261
00:28:29,888 --> 00:28:32,357
Hey. What do you think you're flying.
A kangaroo?

262
00:28:53,208 --> 00:28:55,882
That's tough luck. You missed them.
Now. Put her down.

263
00:29:12,888 --> 00:29:17,644
- What kind of a landing do you call that?
- I'm sorry. Sir. I got confused.

264
00:29:18,408 --> 00:29:22,163
Every time I take you doctors upstairs.
You pat me in the face with a spade.

265
00:29:22,328 --> 00:29:23,682
What have you got against me?

266
00:29:23,848 --> 00:29:26,727
Nothing. The ground's closer
than I thought, that's all.

267
00:29:26,888 --> 00:29:29,198
Slim. You'd never make a flier
in a thousand years.

268
00:29:29,368 --> 00:29:31,962
Doctors are Dodo's by nature.
All of them.

269
00:29:32,168 --> 00:29:34,284
- One thing I want to thank you for.
- What. Sir?

270
00:29:34,448 --> 00:29:37,008
You're the last grasshopper
in this plague of surgeons.

271
00:29:37,168 --> 00:29:38,761
It's an even break to live longer.

272
00:29:38,968 --> 00:29:40,402
- That's all.
- Yes. Sir.

273
00:29:46,528 --> 00:29:48,599
-Hello.

274
00:29:48,768 --> 00:29:51,567
Sorry. But here's another grasshopper.

275
00:29:53,888 --> 00:29:57,006
Well. Well. What have I done
to deserve this honor?

276
00:29:57,168 --> 00:29:59,159
You took the words
right out of my mouth.

277
00:29:59,328 --> 00:30:00,966
Tired of Honolulu?
Run out of women?

278
00:30:01,128 --> 00:30:04,120
No. No. Things just got a little dull
after you left.

279
00:30:04,288 --> 00:30:05,722
Well. When do I start flying?

280
00:30:05,888 --> 00:30:09,119
I can't imagine a nicer job than teaching
you myself. But I'm too busy.

281
00:30:09,288 --> 00:30:10,722
That's a tough break for me.

282
00:30:10,888 --> 00:30:13,846
We'll try to find an instructor
worthy of your talents.

283
00:30:14,008 --> 00:30:15,681
Hey. Tim.

284
00:30:20,528 --> 00:30:23,407
- How are you. Lieutenant?
- I was all right until now.

285
00:30:23,568 --> 00:30:27,084
Tim. The doctor here wants a pair
of wings so he can visit his ex-patients.

286
00:30:27,248 --> 00:30:29,159
See if you can jam his head
into a cockpit.

287
00:30:29,328 --> 00:30:30,966
Well. I'd be delighted.

288
00:30:31,128 --> 00:30:33,722
Get your flight equipment on
and report to plane 17.

289
00:30:33,888 --> 00:30:36,323
- Don't forget your parachute.
- Thank you. Gentlemen.

290
00:30:36,488 --> 00:30:40,368
I know I can expect the very best
of instruction at your hands.

291
00:30:45,968 --> 00:30:49,484
This is a profanity strainer.
I talk. But you can't talk back.

292
00:30:49,648 --> 00:30:51,685
Very clever.
No home should be without one.

293
00:30:51,848 --> 00:30:54,283
All right. Come on. Get aboard.

294
00:31:09,328 --> 00:31:11,126
You're all set?

295
00:31:34,728 --> 00:31:36,605
All right. You take it.

296
00:31:39,608 --> 00:31:41,519
Fly straight ahead.

297
00:31:41,688 --> 00:31:44,123
Keep your nose on the horizon.
Wings level.

298
00:31:57,968 --> 00:32:00,687
All right. Don't pay any attention to me.

299
00:32:00,848 --> 00:32:03,283
I'm just talking through this thing
for practice.

300
00:32:03,688 --> 00:32:07,727
I said. Handle the controls gently.
Dr. Lee.

301
00:32:08,648 --> 00:32:10,844
A Harvard man should know
how to be gentle.

302
00:33:27,088 --> 00:33:30,399
I've checked a lot of students
in my time. But you're about the worst.

303
00:33:30,608 --> 00:33:33,919
If we weren't officers and gentlemen.
I'd say you stink.

304
00:33:34,608 --> 00:33:38,397
Now. To make a quick recovery.
Put that stick forward. Now. Try it again.

305
00:33:47,648 --> 00:33:49,525
Anytime.

306
00:34:07,088 --> 00:34:08,965
Hey. What's the idea?
Flip her over.

307
00:34:24,208 --> 00:34:25,528
Let go of the stick!

308
00:34:51,088 --> 00:34:53,557
Are you trying to fly
or combine suicide with murder?

309
00:34:53,728 --> 00:34:55,719
Maybe that wouldn't be
such a bad idea.

310
00:34:55,888 --> 00:34:58,004
You told me to put the stick forward.
So I did.

311
00:34:58,168 --> 00:35:01,763
Sure. Right through the instrument board.
Don't use your surgical touch on me.

312
00:35:01,928 --> 00:35:03,362
I wanna collect my pension.

313
00:35:03,528 --> 00:35:06,566
Don't worry. You'll be a burden
on the taxpayers for many years.

314
00:35:06,728 --> 00:35:09,117
You're no better at flying than you are
with a knife.

315
00:35:09,288 --> 00:35:11,359
I'll give you one more chance.
Monday morning.

316
00:35:11,528 --> 00:35:14,566
You flunk that one.
And you're washed-out.

317
00:35:23,968 --> 00:35:26,926
Hey. What's the rush?
You got something lined up in town?

318
00:35:27,088 --> 00:35:30,206
No. It's either get off the station
or get a general court-martial.

319
00:35:30,368 --> 00:35:31,722
General court? What for?

320
00:35:31,888 --> 00:35:35,438
For punching that Joe Blake on the nose.
So long. See you later.

321
00:36:02,808 --> 00:36:04,446
Why don't you learn how to drive!

322
00:36:05,248 --> 00:36:06,727
Why do you drive in your sleep?

323
00:36:06,888 --> 00:36:08,606
You came around with your
eyes shut.

324
00:36:08,808 --> 00:36:12,005
Yeah. Well. You saw me coming.
Why didn't you stop?

325
00:36:12,168 --> 00:36:13,886
You got insurance on that fire truck?

326
00:36:14,048 --> 00:36:16,278
No. They don't write it against
drivers like you.

327
00:36:16,448 --> 00:36:18,439
It'll cost you about 50 bucks
to fix my car.

328
00:36:18,608 --> 00:36:21,600
Fifty bucks? You crazy? You can buy
two of those crates for that.

329
00:36:21,768 --> 00:36:24,362
Well. Then maybe you'd rather
I take it out of your hide.

330
00:36:24,528 --> 00:36:26,838
Yeah. Why don't you try that.

331
00:36:28,888 --> 00:36:30,606
Go get him. Boy.

332
00:36:45,288 --> 00:36:48,599
Sorry. I meant that last one for
somebody else. How are you doing?

333
00:36:48,768 --> 00:36:50,566
All right.

334
00:36:50,968 --> 00:36:55,041
- Say. You throw a mean punch there.
- You too. Where'd you learn that right?

335
00:36:55,208 --> 00:36:57,927
At Yale. I was captain of
the boxing team last year.

336
00:36:58,088 --> 00:37:02,321
Yale? Well. That explains everything.
I'm from Harvard. Put her there.

337
00:37:28,728 --> 00:37:30,560
All right. Take her out alone.

338
00:37:30,728 --> 00:37:32,162
Okay.

339
00:37:32,688 --> 00:37:34,838
Sorry if I made good
and disappointed you.

340
00:37:35,008 --> 00:37:36,919
It's a blow. All right.

341
00:37:37,088 --> 00:37:40,126
Commander, there's just one more
thing I'd like to ask you.

342
00:37:40,288 --> 00:37:42,848
- Yeah?
- Why do you dislike me so much?

343
00:37:43,168 --> 00:37:45,967
Because you're a grandstand player.
And a phony on top of it.

344
00:37:46,128 --> 00:37:49,166
If Swede Larson's death makes you
say that. You're being childish.

345
00:37:49,328 --> 00:37:51,763
His number was up before we got him
to the hospital.

346
00:37:51,928 --> 00:37:54,204
I'm not responsible for his death
and you know it.

347
00:37:54,368 --> 00:37:56,757
- Maybe so.
- Then why don't you quit riding me.

348
00:37:56,928 --> 00:37:58,566
Our jobs are tough enough as it is.

349
00:37:58,768 --> 00:38:01,203
I'll stay out of your way.
And you stay out of mine.

350
00:38:01,648 --> 00:38:03,241
Now, get going.

351
00:38:42,008 --> 00:38:44,477
Hit your left rudder.
Not your right, your left.

352
00:38:44,648 --> 00:38:46,958
You're losing altitude fast.

353
00:38:47,128 --> 00:38:49,085
You're gonna crash.

354
00:38:50,488 --> 00:38:54,118
All right. Come on out.
You died a beautiful death.

355
00:38:55,688 --> 00:38:59,283
This. Gentlemen. Perfectly sums up
today's discussion of blind flying.

356
00:38:59,448 --> 00:39:02,167
This pilot crashed because
he trusted his senses.

357
00:39:02,328 --> 00:39:05,559
His semicircular ear canals
lead him to believe. In the darkness...

358
00:39:05,728 --> 00:39:08,242
he was turning left when he was
turning right.

359
00:39:08,448 --> 00:39:09,927
Never trust your senses.

360
00:39:10,088 --> 00:39:12,398
Trust your instrument board.

361
00:39:17,768 --> 00:39:20,328
Did my demonstration bore you.
Lieutenant Lee?

362
00:39:21,728 --> 00:39:24,322
Oh. Not at all. Sir.
It brought up pleasant memories.

363
00:39:24,488 --> 00:39:27,446
I studied the semicircular canals
in second-year medicine.

364
00:39:27,768 --> 00:39:29,679
Did you. Now?

365
00:39:29,848 --> 00:39:33,682
You also learned all about blind flying
at Harvard. Hopkins and Cambridge.

366
00:39:33,848 --> 00:39:37,682
Oh. Yes. I did quite a bit there. Sir.
In a hopped-up jalopy. Of course.

367
00:39:37,848 --> 00:39:40,362
You must've been the pride and joy
of your professors.

368
00:39:40,568 --> 00:39:42,320
You have no idea how they adored me.

369
00:39:44,008 --> 00:39:45,999
Keep that if you like it.

370
00:39:52,728 --> 00:39:57,279
Dr. Lee and all of you gentlemen.
A flight surgeon has been described...

371
00:39:57,448 --> 00:40:00,008
as a combination of Dutch uncle
and father confessor.

372
00:40:00,448 --> 00:40:02,803
Because he's more
than the pilot's physician...

373
00:40:02,968 --> 00:40:06,438
he's a judge of their fitness to go on
with the work they've chosen.

374
00:40:06,608 --> 00:40:08,838
For this task.
He must be conscientious...

375
00:40:09,008 --> 00:40:12,364
and above all. Humble.
Or he has no business being here.

376
00:40:13,408 --> 00:40:17,003
Tomorrow. We'll take up the effect of
anoxia on the electrocardiogram.

377
00:40:17,168 --> 00:40:18,920
Class dismissed.

378
00:40:19,248 --> 00:40:21,967
Boy. You sure got guts talking back
to him like that.

379
00:40:22,128 --> 00:40:23,687
Surly character, isn't he?

380
00:40:23,848 --> 00:40:28,922
I bet a blood sample would show gall.
Bile. With a good dash of sulfuric acid.

381
00:40:33,128 --> 00:40:35,244
Here's the one I'm working on now.

382
00:40:35,408 --> 00:40:38,719
- See that strong bulkhead?
- Yeah.

383
00:40:38,888 --> 00:40:42,438
What are the forces that pull
on a diving pilot when he blacks out?

384
00:40:42,608 --> 00:40:43,928
Between 5 and 10 G.

385
00:40:44,088 --> 00:40:47,046
Between five and 10 times
as strong as the pull of gravity.

386
00:40:47,208 --> 00:40:49,279
- Will it be more with faster ships?
- Not much.

387
00:40:49,448 --> 00:40:53,078
If we lick blackout in our present planes.
The answer will be good along time.

388
00:40:56,128 --> 00:40:59,484
I've gone over these chamber
equipment lists. They seem okay to me.

389
00:40:59,888 --> 00:41:01,799
Good evening. Commander.

390
00:41:08,648 --> 00:41:10,161
Who threw that knife?

391
00:41:10,328 --> 00:41:12,558
I did. Came back pretty fast.
Though. Didn't it?

392
00:41:12,728 --> 00:41:16,767
If he spent less energy being bitter
and more on flying. We might get action.

393
00:41:16,928 --> 00:41:18,999
Maybe he has a right to be bitter.

394
00:41:19,168 --> 00:41:22,718
He wrecked his heart using himself
as a guinea pig on high-altitude flights.

395
00:41:22,888 --> 00:41:26,882
Now he can't fly anymore and he's stuck
at a laboratory desk day and night.

396
00:41:27,048 --> 00:41:30,166
Rogers? Used himself as a guinea pig?
- That's right.

397
00:41:31,288 --> 00:41:34,565
He's also the man who doped out
vitamin A for night blindness...

398
00:41:34,728 --> 00:41:36,207
optically correct goggles...

399
00:41:36,368 --> 00:41:38,757
and shoulder safety belts
to stop crash injuries.

400
00:41:39,488 --> 00:41:41,877
As a flight surgeon, he's tops.

401
00:41:42,168 --> 00:41:45,081
Wow. I had no idea.

402
00:41:45,248 --> 00:41:47,444
No. I didn't think you had.

403
00:41:59,048 --> 00:42:01,005
Yes. Come in.

404
00:42:08,568 --> 00:42:10,161
Good evening.

405
00:42:10,888 --> 00:42:13,402
I saw your lights.
So I thought I'd stop by.

406
00:42:13,568 --> 00:42:15,525
What can I do for you. Lieutenant?

407
00:42:15,688 --> 00:42:20,046
Work seems to be piling up on you here.
I was wondering if I can help you with it.

408
00:42:20,208 --> 00:42:23,564
- You might make those blood counts.
- Sure.

409
00:42:33,008 --> 00:42:34,965
These are mixed.

410
00:42:41,568 --> 00:42:43,366
You know. It's...

411
00:42:44,128 --> 00:42:47,007
strange how wrong you can be
about things and people.

412
00:42:48,768 --> 00:42:52,682
I suppose that's because everything's
so confused in the world these days.

413
00:42:52,848 --> 00:42:54,839
You need a jolt to bring you
to your senses.

414
00:42:55,568 --> 00:42:58,242
When you stop to contemplate
some of...

415
00:42:58,408 --> 00:43:01,526
the things you've said and done.
It makes you feel like an idiot.

416
00:43:03,888 --> 00:43:06,687
But I guess it all comes out
in the wash.

417
00:43:06,848 --> 00:43:09,601
It certainly feels good
to be back in a lab.

418
00:43:10,168 --> 00:43:11,567
Cigarette. Doctor?

419
00:43:13,848 --> 00:43:15,566
Thanks. Doctor.

420
00:43:21,248 --> 00:43:24,878
- I was just thinking of another odd thing.
- What's odd?

421
00:43:25,048 --> 00:43:29,360
Of all the tests used for flying aptitude.
No one thought of trying the Rorschach.

422
00:43:30,888 --> 00:43:32,526
What do you know about it?

423
00:43:33,368 --> 00:43:36,520
Well. Just enough to suspect
it might be valuable.

424
00:43:36,688 --> 00:43:39,919
- Don't you agree?
- I agree that we ought to try it.

425
00:43:40,088 --> 00:43:42,318
- We?
- You and I.

426
00:43:42,488 --> 00:43:46,277
You do all the hard work, and I'll take
all the glory. If any. That suit you?

427
00:43:46,448 --> 00:43:48,485
Sure. Any way you want it.

428
00:43:49,128 --> 00:43:51,563
Doctor. I'm disappointed
in my judgment.

429
00:43:51,728 --> 00:43:53,207
I'm beginning to like you.

430
00:43:54,888 --> 00:43:57,482
Doctor. I'm just suffering
a similar disillusionment.

431
00:43:57,648 --> 00:44:00,083
I'm beginning to suspect you're almost
human yourself.

432
00:44:23,208 --> 00:44:25,279
Douglas Lee.

433
00:44:34,408 --> 00:44:36,524
William Lester Keel.

434
00:44:42,328 --> 00:44:43,648
Good luck to all of you.

435
00:44:43,808 --> 00:44:46,527
The commandant's aide will give you
your orders.

436
00:44:48,248 --> 00:44:51,127
Gregory? Here you are. Slim.

437
00:44:53,648 --> 00:44:57,528
Company commanders. Take charge.
Dismissed.

438
00:45:11,168 --> 00:45:12,488
What did you draw?

439
00:45:12,648 --> 00:45:15,686
Aircraft carrier Saratoga. Pearl Harbor.

440
00:45:15,848 --> 00:45:17,521
I go to Norfolk for assignment.

441
00:45:17,688 --> 00:45:19,759
Well. Soft shoulders and happy landings.

442
00:45:19,928 --> 00:45:21,601
- You too. Norfolk?
- Yeah.

443
00:45:21,768 --> 00:45:24,237
Say. I know a cute redhead there
if you get lonesome.

444
00:45:24,408 --> 00:45:27,207
Well. I'm lonesome now.
Is she big or small?

445
00:45:27,368 --> 00:45:29,325
Well. She's sort of... She's...

446
00:45:29,488 --> 00:45:31,684
Oh. What's the difference?
She's cute anyway.

447
00:45:31,848 --> 00:45:33,566
You'll have to give me her address.

448
00:45:45,048 --> 00:45:46,607
What was your luck?

449
00:45:46,768 --> 00:45:49,442
- Honolulu. The Saratoga.
- Not bad.

450
00:45:49,608 --> 00:45:52,964
Not bad at all. But it's along way
from my real interest, research.

451
00:45:53,128 --> 00:45:55,847
That's life. Soon as a man gets
warmed up for research...

452
00:45:56,008 --> 00:45:58,204
he's yanked off for duty.
Never seen it fail.

453
00:45:58,368 --> 00:46:01,599
Yeah. I guess so. Discouraging. Though.
Guess it's one of those things.

454
00:46:01,768 --> 00:46:05,443
- How'd you like to stay as my assistant?
- I'd like to stand on my head.

455
00:46:05,608 --> 00:46:08,760
I asked for you and Washington
okayed it. This just came.

456
00:46:08,928 --> 00:46:10,441
I'm gonna work you half to death.

457
00:46:10,608 --> 00:46:14,238
Research will be in addition to your other
duties: examining cadets and pilots.

458
00:46:14,408 --> 00:46:16,001
You'll wish you'd gone to Waikiki.

459
00:46:16,168 --> 00:46:18,921
- Never mind that. What's step A?
- Our old friend blackout.

460
00:46:19,088 --> 00:46:22,604
- Doctor. I don't know how to thank you.
- I can't hear a word you're saying.

461
00:46:22,768 --> 00:46:25,442
Well. I'll be right with you.

462
00:46:26,288 --> 00:46:27,687
- Here you are.
- Thank you.

463
00:46:27,848 --> 00:46:30,158
- Would you like something to eat?
- No. Thanks.

464
00:46:30,328 --> 00:46:32,604
Would you like a drink?

465
00:46:34,848 --> 00:46:36,805
Pardon me.

466
00:46:38,168 --> 00:46:39,841
Sorry.

467
00:46:41,808 --> 00:46:45,119
- There you are. Mrs. Fisher.
- Thank you. You're so sweet to me.

468
00:46:45,288 --> 00:46:47,279
Don't mention it.

469
00:46:47,808 --> 00:46:50,368
So you're from Baltimore?

470
00:46:51,688 --> 00:46:54,328
- Where's Mr. Fisher? Is he in Baltimore?
- I just lost him.

471
00:46:54,528 --> 00:46:56,838
- I'm sorry.
- I just lost him in Reno.

472
00:46:57,008 --> 00:46:59,284
- I suffered no pain.
- That's different, isn't it?

473
00:46:59,448 --> 00:47:02,327
- It is indeed. Quite different.
- You here all alone?

474
00:47:03,288 --> 00:47:05,848
All alone. Commander.
Until I leave for Honolulu.

475
00:47:06,008 --> 00:47:08,921
- You have friends there?
- Yes. Some very nice friends.

476
00:47:10,328 --> 00:47:13,366
Tell me. Don't you ever get lonesome
traveling alone like this?

477
00:47:13,528 --> 00:47:14,962
Often.

478
00:47:16,368 --> 00:47:19,599
What are you doing for dinner?
Maybe you'd like to have dinner with me.

479
00:47:19,808 --> 00:47:22,846
- That might be arranged.
- Fine. Where would you like to eat?

480
00:47:23,008 --> 00:47:26,922
Why. I don't know. My hotel is as good
as any place. It's quite convenient.

481
00:47:27,088 --> 00:47:29,728
- Swell, Mrs. Fisher.
- I think you can call me Linda.

482
00:47:30,168 --> 00:47:32,159
- Thanks. I'm Joe.
- Hello. Joe.

483
00:47:32,328 --> 00:47:33,921
Hi. Linda.

484
00:47:36,688 --> 00:47:38,759
- How about another drink?
- I'd love it.

485
00:47:38,928 --> 00:47:41,124
I'll be back in a minute. Linda.

486
00:47:41,888 --> 00:47:44,767
- Pardon me.
- Oh. Sorry.

487
00:47:48,448 --> 00:47:50,439
- Hello. Bill.
- Hello. Doug.

488
00:47:50,608 --> 00:47:52,246
- Hello. Dr. Lee.
- Hello. Mrs. Silvers.

489
00:47:52,408 --> 00:47:54,001
- Nice of you to drop in.
- Thank you.

490
00:47:54,168 --> 00:47:57,160
- May I introduce you around?
- No. I think I know almost everyone.

491
00:47:57,328 --> 00:48:00,446
- Circulate. Have fun.
- Thanks. I'll put my hat over here.

492
00:48:01,328 --> 00:48:04,161
- Hello. Tim.
- Why. Doug. How are you?

493
00:48:14,688 --> 00:48:17,726
- Hello. You beast.
- Sugar! No kicking. Now.

494
00:48:17,888 --> 00:48:20,767
Not yet. You know. It's strange.
When I woke up this morning...

495
00:48:20,928 --> 00:48:22,919
Hurry knew something nice would
happen today.

496
00:48:23,088 --> 00:48:25,125
- Well. So did l. And this must be it.
- Shake.

497
00:48:36,448 --> 00:48:39,486
- Aren't you going to kiss me?
- Oh. Yes. Darling. How are you?

498
00:48:39,688 --> 00:48:42,487
- What are you doing here?
- I'm stationed here. How about you?

499
00:48:42,648 --> 00:48:45,800
You didn't answer my letters.
I was going to Honolulu to see you.

500
00:48:46,288 --> 00:48:48,040
Darling. I'm divorced.

501
00:48:48,208 --> 00:48:50,722
Charlie now belongs to the ages.
Isn't that pleasant?

502
00:48:50,888 --> 00:48:53,118
- Oh. That's wonderful.
- Come on. Let's sit down.

503
00:48:53,288 --> 00:48:56,963
- Oh, Dr. Lee, this is Commander...
- Blake.

504
00:48:57,128 --> 00:48:58,846
- Blake.
- We know each other.

505
00:48:59,008 --> 00:49:00,521
Sure. We're old friends.

506
00:49:00,728 --> 00:49:04,039
Then give my precious a drink.
The commander and I were going...

507
00:49:04,208 --> 00:49:06,848
to dine together tonight.
And you must come with us.

508
00:49:07,008 --> 00:49:10,319
Doug and I are old friends too.
But very old friends.

509
00:49:10,648 --> 00:49:13,322
I helped to cheer him up in Honolulu.

510
00:49:13,488 --> 00:49:17,197
- You certainly did.
- You're such a beast. But so sweet.

511
00:49:17,368 --> 00:49:19,644
And here I go throwing myself
at you again.

512
00:49:20,968 --> 00:49:22,686
Come on. Let's get out of here.

513
00:49:25,128 --> 00:49:26,448
Come on. Commander...

514
00:49:26,608 --> 00:49:29,521
Blake. No. You two run along.
I remembered I have watch tonight.

515
00:49:29,688 --> 00:49:31,804
How unpleasant.
Well. I'll go powder my nose...

516
00:49:31,968 --> 00:49:36,041
tell our hostess a customary lie and be
right back. Meet you in the hall, Doug.

517
00:49:36,208 --> 00:49:39,485
Why am I such a chump
where you're concerned?

518
00:49:42,248 --> 00:49:45,957
If you had an engagement with the lady.
Don't let me stand in your way.

519
00:49:46,128 --> 00:49:48,438
Too bad there are no women on
the selection board.

520
00:49:48,608 --> 00:49:50,838
You'd be an admiral inside of a year.

521
00:49:52,888 --> 00:49:55,482
All right. Come on with the box.

522
00:49:57,648 --> 00:50:00,037
She's got recording instruments
and a movie camera...

523
00:50:00,208 --> 00:50:03,724
to photograph your faces while you're
unconscious. Just turn the switch.

524
00:50:03,888 --> 00:50:05,526
What? No bathtub? No hostess?

525
00:50:05,688 --> 00:50:07,679
No. You'll have to furnish
your own hostess.

526
00:50:07,848 --> 00:50:10,078
From what I hear.
You're the guy who can do it.

527
00:50:10,248 --> 00:50:13,240
Oh. You have. Eh?
Well. Every knock's a boost, you know.

528
00:50:17,728 --> 00:50:19,639
I understand I'm flying
for you gentlemen.

529
00:50:19,848 --> 00:50:22,237
Nice way to spend my time.
I haven't had much to do.

530
00:50:22,408 --> 00:50:26,367
Just training the cadets, flying at night
and... ls Casanova in on this?

531
00:50:26,528 --> 00:50:29,441
- Dr. Lee will act as medical observer.
- You gonna be the pilot?

532
00:50:29,888 --> 00:50:31,765
You can't feel worse about it than I do.

533
00:50:32,048 --> 00:50:34,358
If that's so. Why not give the job
to someone else?

534
00:50:34,528 --> 00:50:36,724
My group was ordered
to send a pilot for a test.

535
00:50:36,888 --> 00:50:39,607
In a good outfit, the skipper does it.
What are the orders?

536
00:50:39,768 --> 00:50:42,487
Service dives to terminal velocity.
Nine-G pullouts.

537
00:50:42,648 --> 00:50:45,208
On the first one.
Tense your muscles from head to toe...

538
00:50:45,368 --> 00:50:47,803
pull your bellies in hard,
yell as loud as you can.

539
00:50:47,968 --> 00:50:50,164
We want to see if that slows
or stops blackouts.

540
00:50:50,328 --> 00:50:52,558
- All right. You ready?
- Yeah.

541
00:50:52,728 --> 00:50:55,447
All right. Men. Pull her out.

542
00:51:51,288 --> 00:51:54,804
Now we're at 15.000 feet
and leveling off.

543
00:51:55,728 --> 00:51:57,878
Here's the dive.

544
00:52:05,728 --> 00:52:07,639
Twelve thousand.

545
00:52:08,288 --> 00:52:09,608
Nine thousand.

546
00:52:10,688 --> 00:52:12,645
Five thousand.

547
00:52:12,808 --> 00:52:16,039
Now we're pulling out.
Still yelling.

548
00:52:16,968 --> 00:52:18,959
Here's the blackout.

549
00:52:37,008 --> 00:52:39,966
Well. There you are.
The yelling didn't help at all.

550
00:52:40,128 --> 00:52:43,246
- Your blackout was slower.
- Well. What does that prove?

551
00:52:43,408 --> 00:52:46,241
I think we're on the right track.
But we overlooked something.

552
00:52:46,408 --> 00:52:47,921
Yeah. A way to stop blackouts.

553
00:52:48,088 --> 00:52:50,238
Might as well run a Mickey Mouse
as that stuff.

554
00:52:50,408 --> 00:52:52,797
Look. I want to tell you something
about that dive.

555
00:52:52,968 --> 00:52:55,323
When we were pulling out of it.
I was bending over.

556
00:52:55,488 --> 00:52:57,604
My camera was stuck
and I was trying to fix it.

557
00:52:57,768 --> 00:53:01,159
- I didn't black out. Just went hazy.
- Bending over? What could that do?

558
00:53:01,528 --> 00:53:04,964
I don't know. Maybe it's equalizing
the pull, something like that.

559
00:53:05,128 --> 00:53:07,881
- Meeting gravity halfway.
Possible. But not probable.

560
00:53:08,768 --> 00:53:10,998
Bending over puts the heart
level with the brain.

561
00:53:11,168 --> 00:53:13,079
It might hold the blood above
heart level.

562
00:53:13,248 --> 00:53:15,444
Next time. Try bending
over low as you can.

563
00:53:15,608 --> 00:53:17,201
First it's yells, then it's bends.

564
00:53:17,408 --> 00:53:19,240
Maybe we should try ski jumping next.

565
00:53:19,408 --> 00:53:21,968
Wait a minute. It may be a guess.
But it's worth trying.

566
00:53:22,128 --> 00:53:25,200
Sit down. I'll show you
the physiological principle involved.

567
00:53:29,608 --> 00:53:31,406
Well. Come out of the test tube. Men.

568
00:53:31,568 --> 00:53:33,844
- Fifty cadets are waiting for examination.
- Right.

569
00:53:34,008 --> 00:53:35,362
Well. Back to earth again.

570
00:53:35,528 --> 00:53:39,726
Now you know how Einstein feels when
he has to add up the household bills.

571
00:53:42,088 --> 00:53:44,557
Take your places for inspection.

572
00:53:45,728 --> 00:53:48,083
All right. Come on.
Take them over here.

573
00:53:57,128 --> 00:53:59,005
- How many are there?
- About 30. sir.

574
00:53:59,168 --> 00:54:02,160
General physical.
Heart. Lungs. Height. Weight. Index.

575
00:54:02,328 --> 00:54:04,604
- Take the ear examination.
- All right. Shirts off!

576
00:54:04,768 --> 00:54:07,123
All right. Gentlemen. Give way. Please.

577
00:54:08,248 --> 00:54:11,001
- More civilians?
- Yes. Sir.

578
00:54:12,328 --> 00:54:13,648
Remember me, sir?

579
00:54:13,808 --> 00:54:16,960
Lucky. Pearl Harbor. I've just been
detailed to be your assistant.

580
00:54:17,128 --> 00:54:19,597
Remember you?
You're a window in the house of my life.

581
00:54:19,768 --> 00:54:21,679
Good to see you.
Glad you got transferred.

582
00:54:21,888 --> 00:54:24,641
So am l. Sir. I'm a new man
since I got away from my wife.

583
00:54:24,808 --> 00:54:26,924
I feel 10 years younger.
I'm putting on weight.

584
00:54:27,088 --> 00:54:28,999
Lucky. Come over here.

585
00:54:30,728 --> 00:54:32,765
It's sure nice to be back with you again.

586
00:54:32,928 --> 00:54:34,441
Thanks. Lucky. Right back at you.

587
00:54:34,608 --> 00:54:36,997
There's a babe in the pay office
looking for you.

588
00:54:37,168 --> 00:54:39,921
- A babe?
- Yeah. A blond with a Brooklyn accent.

589
00:54:40,088 --> 00:54:42,284
She's getting an allotment blank
for your pay.

590
00:54:42,648 --> 00:54:46,687
My wife! That can't be!
She couldn't have swum from Honolulu.

591
00:54:46,848 --> 00:54:50,159
I wouldn't put it past her.
Sir. I gotta hide right away.

592
00:54:50,328 --> 00:54:51,921
This can happen to the best of men.

593
00:54:52,088 --> 00:54:53,601
- Go right ahead.
- Thank you. Sir.

594
00:54:53,768 --> 00:54:56,044
Head her off. Stop her!
Give me a break. Will you?

595
00:54:56,208 --> 00:54:57,721
Where are you going to hide?

596
00:54:57,888 --> 00:54:59,447
How about the Isolation Ward?

597
00:54:59,608 --> 00:55:02,202
Lieutenant. You got genius.
Come on!

598
00:55:02,368 --> 00:55:04,405
Yeah. But. Lucky. Can't you...?

599
00:55:16,128 --> 00:55:17,607
Where is he? Where's my husband?

600
00:55:17,768 --> 00:55:19,088
- Mrs. James?
- In person.

601
00:55:19,248 --> 00:55:21,842
He's in there. But you can't go in.
He's a very sick man.

602
00:55:22,008 --> 00:55:24,284
He'll be a lot sicker
when I get through with him.

603
00:55:24,448 --> 00:55:28,760
I hate to tell you this.
But they're afraid he's got:

604
00:55:28,928 --> 00:55:32,125
If that ever gets in the arm. The whole:

605
00:55:32,288 --> 00:55:33,562
The neck starts:

606
00:55:33,728 --> 00:55:35,560
Comes down the... on the racetrack.

607
00:55:35,728 --> 00:55:40,245
And any time you go into... the... and:

608
00:55:40,408 --> 00:55:41,728
It's very serious.

609
00:55:41,888 --> 00:55:44,038
Whatever that is.
It's too good for him.

610
00:55:44,248 --> 00:55:47,001
Don't get too close.
It's very contagious.

611
00:55:48,288 --> 00:55:50,438
You see. Ma'am.
How it comes and goes?

612
00:55:50,768 --> 00:55:54,124
- And so will l.
- And so will l.

613
00:55:58,408 --> 00:56:00,160
Head up.

614
00:56:01,288 --> 00:56:03,086
All right. Down again.
Feel dizzy?

615
00:56:03,248 --> 00:56:05,922
- Yes. Sir.
- It's all right, Abbott.

616
00:56:06,088 --> 00:56:09,080
- It's a perfectly normal reaction.
- Oh. Thank you. Sir.

617
00:56:09,248 --> 00:56:10,568
- Feel all right?
- Yes, sir.

618
00:56:10,728 --> 00:56:13,288
I can see you are.
Report to the training office.

619
00:56:13,608 --> 00:56:16,361
- Thank you. Sir.
- Who's next? You"?

620
00:56:21,168 --> 00:56:23,205
Well. It's a small world. Isn't it?

621
00:56:23,368 --> 00:56:24,688
Yes. Sir.

622
00:56:24,848 --> 00:56:27,727
- Getting plenty of exercise lately?
- Yes. Sir. Too much, sir.

623
00:56:27,888 --> 00:56:29,208
That's good.

624
00:56:29,368 --> 00:56:31,644
If one eye sees higher.
Which would you land with?

625
00:56:31,808 --> 00:56:33,128
The good one, sir.

626
00:56:33,288 --> 00:56:35,962
Better keep your left up.
Or you won't have a good one.

627
00:56:36,128 --> 00:56:37,846
I won't forget that. Sir.

628
00:56:38,008 --> 00:56:40,921
- What's your middle name?
- Thomas. John Thomas Anthony Ill. Sir.

629
00:56:41,088 --> 00:56:43,921
Born Hempstead. New York.
June the 12th, anno Domini 1919.

630
00:56:44,088 --> 00:56:47,524
This is 1941. San Diego. California.
9:30 a.m., sir.

631
00:56:48,008 --> 00:56:49,726
Very good.

632
00:56:50,528 --> 00:56:52,519
Make a note. Mentally alert...

633
00:56:52,688 --> 00:56:55,328
fresh as a new-laid egg.
Well. An egg anyway.

634
00:56:55,488 --> 00:56:57,877
Favorite sports: automobile racing
and boxing. Ready?

635
00:56:58,048 --> 00:57:00,278
- Yes. Sir.
- Here you go.

636
00:57:02,048 --> 00:57:05,245
Head down! Hold them. Yale!

637
00:57:07,688 --> 00:57:10,487
He says he's practically got the stick
between his teeth now.

638
00:57:10,648 --> 00:57:12,605
All right. Cut the motor.

639
00:57:14,448 --> 00:57:15,768
Why don't you be practical.

640
00:57:15,928 --> 00:57:19,125
You can't use your bending-over routine
without changing the cockpit.

641
00:57:19,288 --> 00:57:21,359
How can a pilot aim with his head
bent down?

642
00:57:21,528 --> 00:57:24,122
Well. He might try a periscope
or a Ouija board.

643
00:57:24,288 --> 00:57:27,485
Can you design a bomber so the pilot
can lie down and aim the bomb...

644
00:57:27,648 --> 00:57:30,447
- ...through the nose of the ship?
- Who's it for? Buck Rogers?

645
00:57:30,608 --> 00:57:33,521
Seriously. Can it be done?
- I suppose a pilot could lie down...

646
00:57:33,688 --> 00:57:36,999
and use auxiliary controls during
the dive. But it sounds silly to me.

647
00:57:37,208 --> 00:57:39,961
Things are tough when a pilot
has to fly on his stomach.

648
00:57:40,128 --> 00:57:42,722
I'll ask the design section.
But I'm sure they'll send...

649
00:57:42,888 --> 00:57:45,402
an order transferring me
to a nut house.

650
00:57:45,568 --> 00:57:48,082
When you two figure out
your next move. Let me know.

651
00:57:48,248 --> 00:57:49,568
I'll be down in Squadron 2.

652
00:57:49,768 --> 00:57:51,839
Gentlemen. I have a solution
to your problem.

653
00:57:52,008 --> 00:57:55,080
Provide each dive-bombing pilot
with an old-fashioned stiff collar.

654
00:57:55,248 --> 00:57:59,526
That will choke him and keep the blood
from rushing from his brain. So long.

655
00:58:00,328 --> 00:58:03,446
Very funny.
Very funny.

656
00:58:03,608 --> 00:58:05,884
“High. Tight. Old-fashioned stiff collar.“

657
00:58:06,048 --> 00:58:10,246
What that guy needs is a high. Tight.
Old-fashioned whack over the head.

658
00:58:10,448 --> 00:58:12,166
Stiff collar.

659
00:58:12,928 --> 00:58:14,919
- Hey.
- What?

660
00:58:15,088 --> 00:58:17,364
What that half-wit just said
about a collar...

661
00:58:17,528 --> 00:58:19,917
except it's not a collar.
It's a belt. Understand?

662
00:58:20,088 --> 00:58:21,761
- Frankly. No.
- Look. Lance...

663
00:58:21,928 --> 00:58:24,920
you make a belt that fits around here.
It's rubber. Pneumatic.

664
00:58:25,088 --> 00:58:26,806
Just before the dive. You inflate it.

665
00:58:26,968 --> 00:58:29,528
That will push the stomach up
under the ribs. Like this:

666
00:58:29,688 --> 00:58:31,725
Compress the whole upper part
of the abdomen.

667
00:58:31,888 --> 00:58:34,357
That will keep the blood
above heart level.

668
00:58:37,048 --> 00:58:38,925
Come on. Lucky. Hurry up.

669
00:58:39,088 --> 00:58:41,841
What happens if this glorified corset
ain't right, sir?

670
00:58:42,008 --> 00:58:45,205
You heard the story about the guy
whose parachute didn't open. Right?

671
00:58:45,368 --> 00:58:47,757
- Do you know how to get into it?
- Sure. It's simple.

672
00:58:47,928 --> 00:58:49,521
At least it was when I designed it.

673
00:58:49,688 --> 00:58:52,123
Here. Place me under the bag. Will you?

674
00:58:53,408 --> 00:58:56,161
- That's it.
- This makes me feel right at home. Sir.

675
00:58:56,368 --> 00:58:58,120
How does it work?

676
00:58:58,288 --> 00:59:01,804
This hooks up to the pressure flask in
the cockpit. When you start a dive...

677
00:59:01,968 --> 00:59:04,881
you release the valve. It inflates it.
Does that. We hope.

678
00:59:05,048 --> 00:59:08,006
It works the way it has on the ground.
It ought to be a cinch.

679
00:59:08,168 --> 00:59:09,727
Did you tell Blake I was waiting?

680
00:59:09,928 --> 00:59:13,717
He said he'd be here when he finishes
lining up the National Defense Program.

681
00:59:13,928 --> 00:59:16,397
Oh. He did. Eh?
That's very clever of him.

682
00:59:16,728 --> 00:59:18,446
Pressure belts. Pressure chambers.

683
00:59:18,608 --> 00:59:22,488
Flying's getting to be as tough as my
wife. Pressure on you all the time.

684
00:59:22,648 --> 00:59:24,241
Yeah.

685
00:59:24,408 --> 00:59:27,605
Aren't you going to wait
for the commander, sir?

686
00:59:28,488 --> 00:59:32,447
You're breaking regulations, doctor.
The commander will be awful sore.

687
00:59:32,608 --> 00:59:35,885
Tell him I'll write him a letter
and explain everything.

688
00:59:49,648 --> 00:59:51,764
Joe. Isn't that your test tube
taking off?

689
00:59:54,728 --> 00:59:56,082
Yeah. What's the idea?

690
00:59:56,248 --> 00:59:58,125
Looks like you're being stood up. Pal.

691
00:59:58,288 --> 01:00:02,202
That lamebrain. He can't fly that ship.
There won't be enough left to identify.

692
01:00:13,368 --> 01:00:15,041
Don't blame me if anything happens.

693
01:00:15,208 --> 01:00:17,119
He shouldn't have done it.
I told him that.

694
01:00:17,288 --> 01:00:20,804
I mean. I was gonna tell him that.
But he got away so fast, I couldn't.

695
01:00:20,968 --> 01:00:23,164
He ain't had enough experience
to fly that ship.

696
01:00:23,328 --> 01:00:26,764
- He's heading for the last roundup.
- Pipe down. What's the matter with you?

697
01:02:38,000 --> 01:02:39,752
Nothing. Sir. I'm just neurotic.

698
01:03:22,808 --> 01:03:25,402
Thought you'd meet me with
a crash truck and fire engine?

699
01:03:25,568 --> 01:03:27,923
No. Sir. A whiskbroom and a dustpan.

700
01:03:28,088 --> 01:03:30,967
- Get the instruments. Will you?
- Aye. Aye. Sir.

701
01:03:34,568 --> 01:03:37,879
Works like a charm. I hoisted her
back to 10 G and didn't even get hazy.

702
01:03:38,048 --> 01:03:40,244
I'm afraid to say it.
But we may have something.

703
01:03:40,408 --> 01:03:41,728
I'm not afraid to say it.

704
01:03:41,888 --> 01:03:44,357
- Aren't you a bit green to dive alone?
- Yeah.

705
01:03:44,568 --> 01:03:46,798
Ground's hard when you
bounce a plane off of it.

706
01:03:47,088 --> 01:03:48,999
But you see. With this belt. You won't.

707
01:03:49,208 --> 01:03:51,677
Some real pilot better check it
before we get excited.

708
01:03:51,888 --> 01:03:53,640
Of course we're gonna check on it.

709
01:03:53,808 --> 01:03:56,800
Test it. Send it to Washington.
Ask them to equip other groups...

710
01:03:56,968 --> 01:03:59,357
- ...so they can check it.
- Fine. I hope it works out.

711
01:03:59,528 --> 01:04:01,485
I envied you up there. Doug.

712
01:04:01,648 --> 01:04:04,766
Being glued to the ground.
I feel as if I'm doing only half the job.

713
01:04:04,928 --> 01:04:07,647
What are you talking about?
You do more than any two of us.

714
01:04:07,808 --> 01:04:10,527
It's funny how a guy's mind works
when he's up there flying.

715
01:04:10,688 --> 01:04:13,885
Just before I put her into that dive.
I kept thinking to myself:

716
01:04:14,048 --> 01:04:16,437
"There's two kinds of blackout
this belt may whip."

717
01:04:16,608 --> 01:04:19,760
Our kind and the sort they're having
over London right now.“

718
01:04:21,968 --> 01:04:22,968
Up.

719
01:04:23,128 --> 01:04:24,880
Down. Up.

720
01:04:25,048 --> 01:04:27,278
- Down. Up.
- Can we have a little music with this?

721
01:04:27,448 --> 01:04:30,600
Down. Sure. What do you want?
Some boogie-woogie? Up.

722
01:04:30,768 --> 01:04:33,920
Down. That's enough.
Sit down. Relax.

723
01:04:34,088 --> 01:04:37,524
- Let me see the chart. Will you?
- Here.

724
01:04:39,368 --> 01:04:42,599
All right. Your Schneider index
seems too good to be true these days.

725
01:04:42,768 --> 01:04:44,884
The result of clean living
and high thinking.

726
01:04:45,048 --> 01:04:46,368
Commander?

727
01:04:46,528 --> 01:04:49,964
Dr. Rogers. How long do I have to keep
on taking these Schneiders anyway?

728
01:04:50,128 --> 01:04:52,642
I know it's a nuisance.
But we have to track changes...

729
01:04:52,808 --> 01:04:54,242
in pulse and blood pressure.

730
01:04:54,408 --> 01:04:57,048
It's one way of determining
if you should continue flying.

731
01:04:57,208 --> 01:05:00,439
I think it's a lot of bunk.
Come on. Hill.

732
01:05:02,648 --> 01:05:04,366
Is that all?

733
01:05:07,088 --> 01:05:09,602
Look. Washington's approved the belt
for further tests.

734
01:05:09,768 --> 01:05:11,964
- It has? Swell.
Congratulations, doctor.

735
01:05:12,128 --> 01:05:14,722
Washington doesn't care
what it approves of these days.

736
01:05:14,928 --> 01:05:16,760
When do we go?
When do we start testing?

737
01:05:16,968 --> 01:05:19,687
A couple carriers are due next month
for a bombing problem.

738
01:05:19,848 --> 01:05:23,125
Couldn't be better. That'll give us
a chance to try it in group action.

739
01:05:23,288 --> 01:05:25,802
- Better take a look at that chart.
- Come on. Tim.

740
01:05:25,968 --> 01:05:28,244
Go on and take those charts
out of my hair.

741
01:05:28,448 --> 01:05:30,644
Tim. I'd like to see you for a minute.

742
01:05:30,808 --> 01:05:32,799
What's the matter?
Haven't I bounced enough?

743
01:05:33,008 --> 01:05:34,425
You better be in on this too. Joe.

744
01:05:36,248 --> 01:05:38,524
Well. Sounds like a tea party.

745
01:05:44,408 --> 01:05:46,399
Hey. Lucky. She's back again.

746
01:05:46,568 --> 01:05:49,082
Why don't somebody tell me
when it's payday?

747
01:05:49,248 --> 01:05:52,161
- Here we go again. Boys!
- Hey. Look. You better be careful.

748
01:06:04,768 --> 01:06:06,805
He's asleep. Mrs. James.
He had a bad night.

749
01:06:06,968 --> 01:06:09,278
He's got worse ones coming
when he gets better.

750
01:06:09,448 --> 01:06:11,758
We're doing all we can
to get him back on his feet.

751
01:06:11,928 --> 01:06:15,683
Just get him strong enough to sit up. I'll
have more fun beating him on the head.

752
01:06:15,848 --> 01:06:20,763
No. You see. The doctor says he's got:
You see... for the patient's...

753
01:06:20,928 --> 01:06:25,001
and they get themselves laying in bed:

754
01:06:25,168 --> 01:06:27,444
- Look. You see where it says “ward“?
- Yeah.

755
01:06:27,648 --> 01:06:33,599
Well. You take the D out
and the... what have you got?

756
01:06:33,768 --> 01:06:36,886
Piston rods.
So you see. It'll never help you.

757
01:06:37,048 --> 01:06:39,278
It will satisfy my soul.

758
01:06:39,448 --> 01:06:41,405
That dame's crazy.

759
01:06:51,408 --> 01:06:53,922
You're not going to recommend me
for a waiver. Are you?

760
01:06:54,088 --> 01:06:56,967
- That's right.
- The service can't lose a pilot like Tim.

761
01:06:57,128 --> 01:06:59,039
Can't you wait.
Give him another Schneider?

762
01:06:59,208 --> 01:07:02,007
- I don't believe that would do any good.
- What do you know?

763
01:07:02,768 --> 01:07:05,282
I can count. Read a watch
and a blood-pressure dial.

764
01:07:05,448 --> 01:07:07,280
- What's wrong with me?
- Pilot fatigue.

765
01:07:07,448 --> 01:07:09,519
As far as flying's concerned,
you're worn-out.

766
01:07:09,728 --> 01:07:11,480
Like the works of an old watch.

767
01:07:11,648 --> 01:07:14,686
What are you talking about?
I can fly as well as I ever could.

768
01:07:14,888 --> 01:07:18,244
Doug's right. There's no argument.
This tells the story.

769
01:07:18,408 --> 01:07:22,003
Here's a composite graph of Schneider
indices in the cases of pilot fatigue.

770
01:07:22,408 --> 01:07:25,799
This is the turning point.
Tense irritability. Nervousness.

771
01:07:26,048 --> 01:07:29,882
You weren't in good shape when you
reported. I ran extra Schneiders on you.

772
01:07:30,048 --> 01:07:33,882
When Dr. Lee took over your group.
I told him to continue with the tests.

773
01:07:34,048 --> 01:07:36,517
Your Schneiders have been following
this curve.

774
01:07:36,688 --> 01:07:40,044
Last week. You were here.
Now you're here.

775
01:07:41,288 --> 01:07:43,928
In my book. That means
you're washed-up with flying.

776
01:07:44,088 --> 01:07:47,080
- For how long?
- Maybe months. Maybe forever.

777
01:07:47,248 --> 01:07:50,718
I can't get by without my flight pay.
I have a wife and kids to support.

778
01:07:50,888 --> 01:07:54,199
- You can't do that on peanuts.
- These things are never easy on anyone.

779
01:07:54,368 --> 01:07:56,359
I won't take any grounding from you.

780
01:07:56,528 --> 01:07:59,486
If the Navy doesn't want experienced
pilots. I know who does.

781
01:07:59,648 --> 01:08:01,400
If you're smart.
Stay out of airplanes.

782
01:08:01,568 --> 01:08:03,684
Stick around a couple months.
See what happens.

783
01:08:03,848 --> 01:08:07,443
Why stick around
and get turned down again?

784
01:08:10,568 --> 01:08:11,842
That's nice going.

785
01:08:12,008 --> 01:08:15,160
I don't know how we ever got along
around here without you.

786
01:08:27,408 --> 01:08:30,526
Don't resign. Tim.
I can fit you into a good ground job.

787
01:08:30,688 --> 01:08:33,248
You know there's no such thing
as a good ground job.

788
01:08:33,408 --> 01:08:36,799
I'd go crazy every time
a plane flew past.

789
01:08:39,048 --> 01:08:40,368
What's this other thing?

790
01:08:40,528 --> 01:08:42,804
Same thing you'd do
if you were kicked out.

791
01:08:42,968 --> 01:08:45,323
- Smoke?
- I got one.

792
01:08:55,608 --> 01:08:58,885
Why didn't you make him
stop flying sooner? Take a rest?

793
01:08:59,048 --> 01:09:01,801
Because flying is like adrenaline
to tense pilots.

794
01:09:01,968 --> 01:09:03,686
Take it away. And they fold up.

795
01:09:03,848 --> 01:09:06,840
So you keep them flying.
Try to coax them back on their feet.

796
01:09:07,008 --> 01:09:10,478
But when the fatigue becomes chronic.
They're usually through.

797
01:09:11,968 --> 01:09:15,563
I know you hated it.
This is a hard business.

798
01:09:15,728 --> 01:09:20,040
A flight surgeon has to face the truth.
And often. It isn't very pleasant.

799
01:09:20,208 --> 01:09:22,040
It certainly isn't.

800
01:09:22,208 --> 01:09:25,405
Well. I guess I should have followed
my mother's fondest wish.

801
01:09:25,568 --> 01:09:27,605
She wanted me to be a violinist.

802
01:09:55,728 --> 01:09:58,368
They all pulled out clean.
Twelve minutes and 15 seconds.

803
01:09:58,528 --> 01:09:59,802
That's really bombing.

804
01:10:00,048 --> 01:10:02,927
A little less doubtful
about the belt now. Commander?

805
01:10:03,088 --> 01:10:05,682
Real pilots used the belt.
Found it's all right.

806
01:10:05,848 --> 01:10:08,317
The belt flew the planes
and aimed the bombs for them.

807
01:10:08,488 --> 01:10:10,923
It'll probably make coffee for them
when they get out.

808
01:10:18,368 --> 01:10:21,087
I think we can forget about blackouts
from now on.

809
01:10:57,088 --> 01:10:59,364
Get stretchers
and take them to sickbay.

810
01:11:00,248 --> 01:11:02,205
It must be high-altitude sickness.

811
01:11:02,368 --> 01:11:04,962
If it is. It's worse than blackout.
The unsolved problem.

812
01:11:05,128 --> 01:11:06,926
Better not stay unsolved for long.

813
01:11:07,088 --> 01:11:10,877
If it does. My mother will get more than
her wish. We'll both wind up violinists.

814
01:11:14,528 --> 01:11:17,202
<i>Royal Air Force fighter, landing on field.</i>

815
01:11:24,568 --> 01:11:26,684
It's the RAF.
He's way off his beat.

816
01:11:26,848 --> 01:11:28,282
Hey. That's a nice job.

817
01:11:28,448 --> 01:11:30,644
I'd hate to have that on my tail
in a dogfight.

818
01:12:00,568 --> 01:12:02,286
- Say. Isn't that Tim Griffin?
- Yeah.

819
01:12:02,448 --> 01:12:03,847
Commander Blake.

820
01:12:04,008 --> 01:12:06,284
- Hi. Fella.
- Hi. Boy.

821
01:12:06,808 --> 01:12:10,767
Commander Blake. Tim's back.
He just brought in that RAF fighter.

822
01:12:14,928 --> 01:12:17,647
- Hi. Tim!
- How are you, Tim?

823
01:12:22,928 --> 01:12:25,397
Hi. Sailor! How are you?

824
01:12:25,728 --> 01:12:28,959
- Well. How are you, sailor?
- Tim. What brought you down here?

825
01:12:29,128 --> 01:12:31,404
I picked it up in L.A..
Ferried it to Canada.

826
01:12:31,568 --> 01:12:33,878
Took a detour to see how
you were doing without me.

827
01:12:34,048 --> 01:12:36,164
We're doing all right.
Look at that uniform.

828
01:12:36,328 --> 01:12:37,762
How do you like that?

829
01:12:37,928 --> 01:12:41,046
They call me the Beau Brummell
of Montreal.

830
01:12:41,208 --> 01:12:43,006
- How about some gas?
- Got a credit card?

831
01:12:43,168 --> 01:12:46,445
- I just sign the bill “Winston C.“
- Okay. Now. Fill her up.

832
01:12:46,608 --> 01:12:49,487
- Don't touch the motor. It's perfect.
- Nothing else, Tim?

833
01:12:49,648 --> 01:12:52,766
- I'll take anything that isn't
nailed down. - How's a spot of tea?

834
01:12:52,928 --> 01:12:54,760
- And a hamburger?
- Right.

835
01:12:57,448 --> 01:13:00,361
Well. Look here.
How are you?

836
01:13:00,528 --> 01:13:01,802
Aren't you pretty.

837
01:13:01,968 --> 01:13:05,086
I'm looking for a beauty contest to enter.

838
01:13:09,808 --> 01:13:12,322
Next month. I go on
transatlantic bomber ferry.

839
01:13:12,488 --> 01:13:15,446
Each pilot flies his own ship over.
One plane brings them back.

840
01:13:15,608 --> 01:13:20,079
It's real dough. A hundred pounds‘ bonus
a hop. And four and five hops a month.

841
01:13:20,248 --> 01:13:21,761
A thousand bucks a month?

842
01:13:21,928 --> 01:13:25,683
Yeah. If any of you guys want a job.
Just let me know.

843
01:13:25,848 --> 01:13:28,237
Hey. What's the lowdown
on the RAF fighter squadrons?

844
01:13:28,408 --> 01:13:30,558
Nobody chases ships anymore.
They're too fast.

845
01:13:30,728 --> 01:13:34,119
You pick out an enemy. Dive on them
and hose them with eight machine guns.

846
01:13:34,288 --> 01:13:37,485
If you don't drop him down. Keep going.
Look for another pushover.

847
01:13:37,648 --> 01:13:40,527
Altitude's the answer.
Forty to 45,000 feet.

848
01:13:40,688 --> 01:13:44,682
The guy on top wins all the marbles.
I've got to roll, Joe. Check.

849
01:13:45,168 --> 01:13:47,125
Oh. No. This one's on Uncle Sam.

850
01:13:47,288 --> 01:13:50,246
You mean. Uncle Joe. Okay.

851
01:13:50,568 --> 01:13:53,208
Oh. Hello. Doctor. You remember me?

852
01:13:53,368 --> 01:13:56,042
Worn-out, rundown “like the works
of an old watch“?

853
01:13:56,208 --> 01:13:58,768
- Sure. How are you?
- Still flying. No thanks to you.

854
01:13:58,928 --> 01:14:01,238
But I thank you
for kicking me into a better job.

855
01:14:01,408 --> 01:14:03,684
I hope all of my mistakes
turn out that well.

856
01:14:03,848 --> 01:14:07,159
They might if your patients get away
from you early enough. I was lucky.

857
01:14:08,288 --> 01:14:10,564
I hope your luck holds. Chum.

858
01:14:10,728 --> 01:14:13,288
In fact. I wish you all the luck
in the world.

859
01:14:13,448 --> 01:14:16,361
Well. Thanks for those few kind words.

860
01:14:17,048 --> 01:14:19,688
Come on. Joe. So long. Sailors.

861
01:14:23,528 --> 01:14:25,405
- Ninety gallons.
- Ninety gallons.

862
01:14:25,568 --> 01:14:28,447
Ninety gallons.
And charge it to Winston C.

863
01:14:28,608 --> 01:14:29,928
Thanks.

864
01:14:30,088 --> 01:14:32,318
I'll smoke one of my own.

865
01:14:38,808 --> 01:14:42,039
- Sort of miss the old gang. Don't you?
- Yep.

866
01:14:43,448 --> 01:14:46,964
The days you and Swede and I flew
together were the happiest in my life.

867
01:14:47,128 --> 01:14:50,120
We can't live them over.
But they're sure swell to look back on.

868
01:14:50,288 --> 01:14:52,006
This is all right.

869
01:14:52,168 --> 01:14:54,842
Great bunch of people up there
and on the other side...

870
01:14:55,008 --> 01:14:56,965
but I'd rather be a pilot
in the Navy...

871
01:14:57,128 --> 01:14:59,563
with you as my skipper
than anything on earth.

872
01:14:59,728 --> 01:15:01,924
Thanks. Tim. Right back at you.

873
01:15:02,088 --> 01:15:06,446
- Say. How have you been feeling. Really?
- Oh. Fine. Fine. Joe.

874
01:15:06,608 --> 01:15:09,964
Of course. I get woozy now and then
after too many hours in the air.

875
01:15:10,128 --> 01:15:12,881
That's why I break these ferry trips up
into short jumps.

876
01:15:13,048 --> 01:15:15,164
Where do you land?
San Francisco or Medford?

877
01:15:15,328 --> 01:15:18,639
I'll go on to Seattle.
That's an easy hop.

878
01:15:19,368 --> 01:15:23,646
- So long. Joe. It's been swell.
- Take care of yourself. Sailor.

879
01:15:28,248 --> 01:15:29,807
Thanks.

880
01:15:55,048 --> 01:16:00,680
RAF fighter. Griffin, pilot.
San Diego for Seattle.

881
01:16:00,848 --> 01:16:06,480
<i>Please notify San Francisco,
Medford and destination.</i>

882
01:16:07,048 --> 01:16:11,724
Expected time of Arrival, 5:10.
That is all.

883
01:16:11,888 --> 01:16:14,402
Let me know when he passes
San Francisco and Medford...

884
01:16:14,568 --> 01:16:16,844
- ...and when he arrives in Seattle.
- Aye. Aye.

885
01:16:40,088 --> 01:16:41,442
Mr. Griffin passed Medford.

886
01:16:41,608 --> 01:16:44,839
Both Seattle and Vancouver are calling
him now. He doesn't answer.

887
01:16:45,008 --> 01:16:47,363
- Thank you. Take over.
- Aye. Aye.

888
01:16:47,528 --> 01:16:49,280
- Larson. Smith.
- Here. Sir.

889
01:16:49,448 --> 01:16:52,440
San Francisco calling Griffin
in RAF lighter.

890
01:16:52,608 --> 01:16:56,647
<i>Medford calling RAF fighter.
Griffin, pilot. Griffin, answer Medford.</i>

891
01:16:56,808 --> 01:16:58,207
Seattle calling Griffin.

892
01:16:58,368 --> 01:17:02,441
This is Vancouver. Griffin, RAF lighter,
answer Vancouver.

893
01:17:03,528 --> 01:17:05,280
San Francisco to Medford.

894
01:17:05,448 --> 01:17:08,645
Have you checked all emergency fields
north of your station?

895
01:17:08,808 --> 01:17:13,723
<i>Medford to San Francisco. It‘s gone out
by Teletype. We‘re on the phone now.</i>

896
01:17:13,888 --> 01:17:18,121
Medford to all stations.
Medford to all stations.

897
01:17:18,288 --> 01:17:22,964
RAF fighter. Griffin, pilot. Attempted
to land at emergency field 26.

898
01:17:23,128 --> 01:17:26,007
He made a normal approach,
but misjudged his altitude...

899
01:17:26,168 --> 01:17:29,399
<i>and hooked a wing against a hangar.
The ship is a washout.</i>

900
01:17:29,568 --> 01:17:32,879
The pilot was instantly killed.
That is all.

901
01:17:33,048 --> 01:17:35,403
San Francisco to all stations.

902
01:17:35,568 --> 01:17:37,878
Resume regular routine.

903
01:18:16,608 --> 01:18:20,841
Think we should've denitrogenated Elmer
before taking him up to 25,000 feet?

904
01:18:21,008 --> 01:18:23,079
He'd look cute riding
a stationary bicycle...

905
01:18:23,248 --> 01:18:25,637
trying to work the nitrogen
out of his system.

906
01:18:25,808 --> 01:18:29,164
I think that whole decompression theory
is much overdone.

907
01:18:29,328 --> 01:18:30,887
I'm inclined to agree with you.

908
01:18:37,848 --> 01:18:39,680
I've heard you want
human guinea pigs...

909
01:18:39,848 --> 01:18:41,885
- ...for your low-pressure research.
- We do.

910
01:18:42,048 --> 01:18:43,641
I'd like to volunteer for the job.

911
01:18:43,808 --> 01:18:46,846
Also as pilot for your high-altitude work.
When you get to it.

912
01:18:47,728 --> 01:18:50,925
That's great. But I thought you felt
our work was a waste of time.

913
01:18:52,368 --> 01:18:54,928
I guess I've been wrong
about a couple of things.

914
01:18:55,088 --> 01:18:58,319
The pressure belt and Tim Griffin.

915
01:18:58,488 --> 01:19:01,799
- Can you use me?
- I'll say we can. We'll let you know.

916
01:19:02,888 --> 01:19:04,526
Thanks.

917
01:19:12,728 --> 01:19:14,048
Start reducing pressure.

918
01:19:21,928 --> 01:19:23,919
A thousand feet.

919
01:19:26,808 --> 01:19:28,685
Five thousand.

920
01:19:30,608 --> 01:19:31,928
Ten thousand.

921
01:19:40,088 --> 01:19:42,398
Twenty-five thousand.

922
01:19:43,648 --> 01:19:46,367
- That's it.
- Elmer can take it.

923
01:19:46,528 --> 01:19:49,725
Take him up to 40.000.
If he's all right, we'll try it on humans.

924
01:19:49,888 --> 01:19:51,799
Okay.

925
01:19:58,168 --> 01:20:01,047
- Good morning.
- Good morning. Sir.

926
01:20:01,248 --> 01:20:04,081
This is human guinea-pig experiment 32.

927
01:20:04,248 --> 01:20:06,524
Its purpose is to study
how the lack of oxygen...

928
01:20:06,688 --> 01:20:09,328
affects your ability
to coordinate rapid movements.

929
01:20:09,488 --> 01:20:13,959
I appreciate your volunteering for this
experiment. And good luck. All right.

930
01:20:36,808 --> 01:20:41,678
Just sit down anywhere. Gentlemen.
And adjust your oximeters on your ear.

931
01:20:46,008 --> 01:20:48,921
That will show the amount of oxygen
in your bloodstream.

932
01:20:49,088 --> 01:20:52,206
Now. I think you understand
about this chamber.

933
01:20:52,368 --> 01:20:55,440
It's for reproducing the conditions
of flying at high altitude.

934
01:20:55,608 --> 01:20:59,363
We do this by pumping out the air inside
and gradually reducing the pressure.

935
01:20:59,528 --> 01:21:02,088
The higher the altitude.
The more trouble you'll have...

936
01:21:02,248 --> 01:21:05,240
coordinating your movements
so that you can fly properly.

937
01:21:08,248 --> 01:21:09,886
We're ready.

938
01:21:10,048 --> 01:21:12,403
Mac's in chair number one.
Abbott's in two.

939
01:21:12,568 --> 01:21:14,241
Anthony's in three.
Blake in four.

940
01:21:16,768 --> 01:21:20,682
- All right. Start reducing pressure.
- Aye. Sir.

941
01:21:27,728 --> 01:21:30,846
Now. Follow the movement of the lights
with your controls.

942
01:21:31,008 --> 01:21:32,965
By lining the green light
with the red...

943
01:21:33,128 --> 01:21:35,039
you indicate your ability
to coordinate.

944
01:21:41,448 --> 01:21:43,678
Five thousand feet.

945
01:21:44,768 --> 01:21:46,805
Five thousand.

946
01:21:47,608 --> 01:21:49,724
Six thousand.

947
01:21:51,408 --> 01:21:53,604
Seven thousand.

948
01:21:55,168 --> 01:21:57,523
Eight thousand.

949
01:21:58,568 --> 01:22:00,002
Nine thousand.

950
01:22:01,968 --> 01:22:03,288
Ten thousand.

951
01:22:05,408 --> 01:22:07,638
Eleven thousand.

952
01:22:08,368 --> 01:22:11,565
The pressure now corresponds
to 12.000 feet.

953
01:22:11,728 --> 01:22:13,127
Put on oxygen masks.

954
01:22:16,008 --> 01:22:17,681
Thirteen thousand.

955
01:22:20,648 --> 01:22:22,047
I don't need any oxygen yet.

956
01:22:27,528 --> 01:22:30,122
Tough guy Anthony says
he doesn't need oxygen.

957
01:22:30,688 --> 01:22:32,998
All right. But watch him.

958
01:22:33,688 --> 01:22:35,964
Sixteen thousand.

959
01:22:42,648 --> 01:22:44,446
Ls Joe's equipment properly set?

960
01:22:46,848 --> 01:22:49,886
- Nineteen thousand.
- Yes. It is.

961
01:22:54,288 --> 01:22:55,562
Twenty thousand feet.

962
01:22:55,928 --> 01:22:58,920
<i>Twenty thousand feet. Going up.</i>

963
01:23:01,208 --> 01:23:03,518
Twenty-one thousand.

964
01:23:06,608 --> 01:23:08,997
Twenty-two thousand.

965
01:23:16,528 --> 01:23:19,122
Twenty-four thousand.

966
01:23:21,568 --> 01:23:24,162
Twenty-live thousand.

967
01:23:25,208 --> 01:23:26,881
Take a deep breath.

968
01:23:29,208 --> 01:23:31,199
Once more.

969
01:23:32,408 --> 01:23:34,797
Twenty-seven thousand.

970
01:23:37,208 --> 01:23:38,721
Twenty-eight thousand.

971
01:23:38,888 --> 01:23:40,208
How do you feel. Tough guy?

972
01:23:41,848 --> 01:23:44,647
- Twenty-nine thousand.
- Never felt better.

973
01:23:46,408 --> 01:23:47,921
Thirty thousand feet.

974
01:23:51,608 --> 01:23:53,884
Thirty-one thousand.

975
01:23:56,728 --> 01:23:58,924
Thirty-two thousand.

976
01:24:07,248 --> 01:24:08,647
Better check Joe again.

977
01:24:12,008 --> 01:24:14,477
Thirty-live thousand.

978
01:24:17,168 --> 01:24:20,001
- Thirty-six thousand.
- That better?

979
01:24:21,088 --> 01:24:23,921
- You said it.
- Thirty-seven thousand.

980
01:24:24,088 --> 01:24:28,844
Lance. That setting wasn't adequate
for a man of his size. I increased it.

981
01:24:31,808 --> 01:24:35,358
We're just under 40.000 feet.
Let me hear heartbeats.

982
01:24:52,208 --> 01:24:53,528
Let me hear Blake's.

983
01:25:11,568 --> 01:25:15,607
All right. Give me another one. Someone
who‘s had a full supply of oxygen.

984
01:25:29,128 --> 01:25:30,846
Cut the motor.

985
01:25:34,248 --> 01:25:35,602
Forty thousand.

986
01:25:35,768 --> 01:25:38,567
Now. Let's see how long
you can stand this pressure.

987
01:26:30,728 --> 01:26:33,038
Start to increase pressure.

988
01:26:37,248 --> 01:26:39,205
We're coming down. Watch your ears.

989
01:26:53,488 --> 01:26:55,286
What a hop.

990
01:26:58,288 --> 01:26:59,608
Start rubbing it hard.

991
01:27:02,528 --> 01:27:04,519
Aeroembolism.

992
01:27:04,688 --> 01:27:07,601
Feels like a duffel bag full of jelly.

993
01:27:07,768 --> 01:27:09,884
All right. Try it now.

994
01:27:10,488 --> 01:27:12,525
- Is that better?
- Yeah.

995
01:27:12,688 --> 01:27:14,918
Report to the lab
for x-ray pictures.

996
01:27:15,088 --> 01:27:18,399
Thank you very much, gentlemen.
For being such cooperative rabbits.

997
01:27:18,568 --> 01:27:21,321
I wish we could reward you.
But we're fresh out of lettuce.

998
01:27:27,248 --> 01:27:28,921
Look straight.

999
01:27:35,448 --> 01:27:37,007
All right.

1000
01:27:50,928 --> 01:27:53,647
There's a suggestion of gas bubbles
in this knee joint too.

1001
01:27:53,808 --> 01:27:57,403
Every case we've tested has shown
strong evidence of bubble formation.

1002
01:27:57,568 --> 01:28:00,401
The higher the altitude.
The stronger the evidence becomes.

1003
01:28:00,568 --> 01:28:03,037
See? No mistaking that.

1004
01:28:03,568 --> 01:28:07,084
Maybe flying should just be restricted
to 35.000 feet, and let it go at that.

1005
01:28:07,248 --> 01:28:09,159
We can't. In flying. The sky's the limit.

1006
01:28:09,328 --> 01:28:12,286
A fighter has to be able
to get above the other fella.

1007
01:28:12,448 --> 01:28:14,883
If you restrict altitude.
You're not making progress.

1008
01:28:15,048 --> 01:28:18,166
That's right. We've got to find
the cause of high-altitude sickness.

1009
01:28:18,328 --> 01:28:20,842
Whether it's partly bubbles
or entirely lack of oxygen.

1010
01:28:21,008 --> 01:28:24,638
All we've been able to find out is that
pilots need oxygen above 12,000 feet.

1011
01:28:24,808 --> 01:28:28,164
We don't know what high-altitude
sickness is, but we know how to stop it.

1012
01:28:28,328 --> 01:28:31,400
Keep the pilots at sea-level pressure.
No matter how high they go.

1013
01:28:31,568 --> 01:28:34,321
- When is that pressure-cabin job ready?
- Four. Five days.

1014
01:28:34,488 --> 01:28:37,719
Your pressure cabin might be fine
for big ships. Weight doesn't matter.

1015
01:28:37,888 --> 01:28:41,483
For the small fighter, the extra weight
will knock 5000 feet off your ceiling.

1016
01:28:41,648 --> 01:28:45,357
- We'll find out. Let's see blood counts.
- You need a close-fitting pressure suit.

1017
01:28:45,528 --> 01:28:48,202
You can't put a pilot in armor.
He'd be too stiff to move.

1018
01:28:48,368 --> 01:28:51,759
- He could move if it had flexible joints.
- Ventilation would be a problem.

1019
01:28:51,928 --> 01:28:53,646
The pilot would snuff out like that.

1020
01:28:53,808 --> 01:28:56,687
- I don't believe you can do it.
- Why does it have to be armor?

1021
01:28:56,848 --> 01:28:59,522
Wait a minute.
I think Blake's got something there.

1022
01:28:59,688 --> 01:29:03,124
Look. If we design it like this.
On the principle of a diving suit...

1023
01:29:03,288 --> 01:29:06,565
with flexible joints here.
Yet capable of holding oxygen inside...

1024
01:29:06,728 --> 01:29:09,163
Hurry think we'll have something. Look.

1025
01:29:10,288 --> 01:29:12,848
I'd like to work on it with you
if you're willing.

1026
01:29:13,008 --> 01:29:15,841
- It's okay with me.
- While you're knitting your union suit...

1027
01:29:16,008 --> 01:29:19,046
I'll go right ahead
with the pressure-cabin job.

1028
01:29:22,328 --> 01:29:24,080
You're wanted in the office
right away.

1029
01:29:24,248 --> 01:29:26,364
Fifty new cadets are
assigned to your squadron.

1030
01:29:26,528 --> 01:29:29,407
- Who assigned them?
- I don't know. Sir. I didn't.

1031
01:29:29,568 --> 01:29:31,639
Fifty? Why do they keep
shoving them at me?

1032
01:29:31,808 --> 01:29:35,438
What do they think I do? Wave a magic
wand and make fliers out of them?

1033
01:29:36,728 --> 01:29:39,038
Joe's pretty irritable lately.

1034
01:29:39,448 --> 01:29:43,203
You may have noticed it. Joe's
Schneider chart's been missing.

1035
01:29:43,368 --> 01:29:44,642
Yeah. I did.

1036
01:29:44,808 --> 01:29:49,279
I didn't want it known that he's been
on the pilot fatigue curve lately.

1037
01:29:49,448 --> 01:29:53,407
Dropped to two this morning.
He's almost reached the chronic line.

1038
01:29:55,008 --> 01:29:58,080
That means we've got to get another
man for our high-altitude work.

1039
01:29:58,248 --> 01:30:02,287
That might be the worst possible move.
He still has a fair chance for recovery.

1040
01:30:02,448 --> 01:30:05,167
It will be tough on him
after all the work he's done.

1041
01:30:05,328 --> 01:30:06,921
Is he worried about something else?

1042
01:30:07,088 --> 01:30:09,807
No. But I think Griffin's death
hit him pretty hard.

1043
01:30:09,968 --> 01:30:12,642
Besides. He's tense, nervous as a cat.
Works all the time.

1044
01:30:12,808 --> 01:30:15,527
- Doesn't know how to play.
- You could help him with that.

1045
01:30:15,688 --> 01:30:18,487
Me? I doubt that.

1046
01:30:18,648 --> 01:30:20,127
Wait a minute.

1047
01:30:20,288 --> 01:30:22,245
I've got a clue.

1048
01:30:22,608 --> 01:30:24,360
- Maybe I can, at that.
- Good.

1049
01:30:24,528 --> 01:30:26,201
Hey. Lucky.

1050
01:30:26,848 --> 01:30:28,759
- I've got a job for you.
- Aye. Aye. Sir.

1051
01:30:30,768 --> 01:30:32,042
Hey. Lucky. Lower your boom.

1052
01:30:32,208 --> 01:30:35,439
Tugboat Annie's back again
with a full head of steam.

1053
01:30:35,808 --> 01:30:39,199
Ain't a guy got no privacy
in this man's Navy?

1054
01:30:55,648 --> 01:30:57,878
You can't see him, Mrs. James.
He's gotten lower.

1055
01:30:58,048 --> 01:31:00,847
He couldn't get any lower than he was.
Where is the snake?

1056
01:31:01,008 --> 01:31:03,727
- In an oxygen tent with four nurses.
- That sounds like him.

1057
01:31:03,888 --> 01:31:06,641
I bet they're all blonds.
Are they? Are they all blonds?

1058
01:31:06,808 --> 01:31:09,800
No. Male nurses. We're trying
to pull him through the crisis.

1059
01:31:09,968 --> 01:31:13,962
Better get him pulled by next payday.
Or I'm going to the admiral.

1060
01:31:14,128 --> 01:31:15,402
Mrs. James?

1061
01:31:15,568 --> 01:31:17,445
Hurry...

1062
01:31:17,688 --> 01:31:21,727
I was just wondering if I couldn't
sort of help you with the admiral?

1063
01:31:21,888 --> 01:31:23,322
You know him?

1064
01:31:23,488 --> 01:31:26,446
Truthfully. No. But he and a friend
of mine are very good pals.

1065
01:31:26,608 --> 01:31:28,997
I thought we could discuss it
somewhere sometime.

1066
01:31:29,168 --> 01:31:31,284
Perhaps tonight for dinner? About 7?

1067
01:31:31,448 --> 01:31:33,485
- Well. I don't know.
- 7:30?

1068
01:31:33,648 --> 01:31:36,686
I suppose it'll be all right.
Seeing how I'm practically a widow.

1069
01:31:36,848 --> 01:31:40,728
Your husband's in a bad way. And we
could discuss the various arrangements.

1070
01:31:40,888 --> 01:31:43,198
Well. I live at the
Blue Horizon Apartments.

1071
01:31:43,368 --> 01:31:47,566
I'll meet you in the lobby.
Make it 7. And please don't be late.

1072
01:31:47,728 --> 01:31:50,288
I'm always on time.
You see. Hurry... for the Navy.

1073
01:31:50,448 --> 01:31:52,325
I can... traditions. You know.

1074
01:31:52,488 --> 01:31:54,320
People talking about the state.

1075
01:31:54,488 --> 01:31:58,163
I walk through... Boy Scouts. But:

1076
01:31:58,328 --> 01:32:03,448
That's nice. So am l.
I'll see you later.

1077
01:32:08,008 --> 01:32:10,443
Okay. Lucky. All clear.

1078
01:32:15,448 --> 01:32:18,600
Hey. What's wrong with you, bud?

1079
01:32:18,768 --> 01:32:20,406
Measles.

1080
01:32:20,568 --> 01:32:22,286
What's yours?

1081
01:32:23,848 --> 01:32:26,078
- Why is this door open?
- Well. I was going...

1082
01:32:26,248 --> 01:32:27,568
What are you doing in there?

1083
01:32:27,728 --> 01:32:31,164
I was checking things to see if
everything's shipshape for inspection.

1084
01:32:31,328 --> 01:32:34,525
There's measles in that ward.
You'll have to stay in Isolation.

1085
01:32:34,688 --> 01:32:37,362
My sister's in town.
And if I could see her tonight...

1086
01:32:37,528 --> 01:32:39,838
then I'd come back
and have my measles in peace.

1087
01:32:40,008 --> 01:32:42,761
You can see her in 21 days.
Take care of him.

1088
01:32:42,928 --> 01:32:46,125
- Aye. Aye. Sir.
- What am I gonna do for 21 days?

1089
01:32:46,288 --> 01:32:48,598
I wouldn't pay any attention
to the captain. Lucky.

1090
01:32:48,768 --> 01:32:52,762
What if you are... and people
bring you...?

1091
01:32:52,928 --> 01:32:56,922
You can have:
What can you lose?

1092
01:32:57,088 --> 01:32:59,762
It's healthy:

1093
01:32:59,928 --> 01:33:01,887
I'll even bring you my socks.
You can darn them.

1094
01:33:03,688 --> 01:33:06,521
You understand that Navy property
is valuable. Don't you?

1095
01:33:06,688 --> 01:33:10,044
You took the risk of cracking up
your plane by landing on field seven.

1096
01:33:10,208 --> 01:33:13,644
- Your orders were clear. Am I right?
- Yes. Sir. But Hurry...

1097
01:33:13,808 --> 01:33:15,446
You haven't answered my question.

1098
01:33:15,648 --> 01:33:19,357
You made the landing in emergency field
number seven against orders. Why?

1099
01:33:19,528 --> 01:33:21,883
I wanted to try landing
in a small field. Sir.

1100
01:33:22,048 --> 01:33:25,120
You tried it and cracked up your plane.
You weren't ready for it.

1101
01:33:25,288 --> 01:33:27,962
I wasn't ready for the wheelbarrow
left on the runway.

1102
01:33:28,128 --> 01:33:30,483
Otherwise. I made a perfect
three-point landing.

1103
01:33:30,648 --> 01:33:34,482
You can try one on the washout board
at 4:00. You're through.

1104
01:33:34,688 --> 01:33:36,645
That's all.

1105
01:33:45,648 --> 01:33:48,686
Too bad about that kid.
He had the makings of a great pilot.

1106
01:33:48,848 --> 01:33:51,727
Yeah. For a circus.
The Navy has no place for stuntmen.

1107
01:33:51,888 --> 01:33:55,847
That's funny. I always thought you did
quite a bit of stunting yourself once.

1108
01:33:56,008 --> 01:33:58,045
Along time ago.
For publicity purposes.

1109
01:33:58,208 --> 01:34:00,040
The Navy has changed since then.

1110
01:34:00,208 --> 01:34:04,042
Well. It just seemed too bad, after all
that time you spent on him. To lose it.

1111
01:34:04,208 --> 01:34:08,202
I'll bet a month's pay that you got your
ears pinned back for the same thing.

1112
01:34:08,368 --> 01:34:11,281
- Who told you that?
- Nobody. That's the kind of guy you are.

1113
01:34:11,448 --> 01:34:14,406
Why don't you give him another chance.
He thinks you're great.

1114
01:34:14,568 --> 01:34:18,402
All you have to do is talk to him
to straighten him out. How about that?

1115
01:34:18,688 --> 01:34:22,647
You're the nosiest guy I ever met.
And it's always in my business.

1116
01:34:24,288 --> 01:34:26,120
- I'll give him one more chance.
- Swell.

1117
01:34:26,288 --> 01:34:30,521
Thanks. And while you're in the same
mood. I'd like to ask one more favor.

1118
01:34:30,688 --> 01:34:32,884
- What is it?
- Remember my pal Linda Fisher?

1119
01:34:33,048 --> 01:34:35,437
She's getting into town with a friend.
Help me out?

1120
01:34:35,608 --> 01:34:38,282
No soap. I got a lot of work to do.

1121
01:34:39,688 --> 01:34:41,042
What's her friend look like?

1122
01:35:03,328 --> 01:35:06,241
I've never known Navy fliers.
But I know lots of Army fliers.

1123
01:35:06,408 --> 01:35:08,160
They're loads of fun.

1124
01:35:08,648 --> 01:35:11,037
That's very interesting.

1125
01:35:14,368 --> 01:35:18,407
- Did you miss me dreadfully?
- Miss you? Oh. I could hardly stand it.

1126
01:35:18,568 --> 01:35:22,482
Isn't that pleasant?
How long have I been gone?

1127
01:35:22,688 --> 01:35:25,487
How long? Must have been weeks.
Wasn't it?

1128
01:35:25,648 --> 01:35:29,767
Weeks? I've been gone for months.
You foul creature.

1129
01:35:29,968 --> 01:35:31,686
You haven't heard a word I've said.

1130
01:35:31,848 --> 01:35:36,240
- Are all Navy men so absent-minded?
- Yeah. No. no.

1131
01:35:37,168 --> 01:35:38,602
Hey. Lee. It just hit me.

1132
01:35:38,768 --> 01:35:41,647
I know how we can control
the pressure and oxygen in that suit.

1133
01:35:41,808 --> 01:35:43,924
Globe valves with fine threads
on the spindles.

1134
01:35:44,088 --> 01:35:47,558
- Wouldn't work, I don't think.
- Yes. It would work. I'll show you.

1135
01:35:49,728 --> 01:35:52,163
- Are they all like that?
- He seems to infect them.

1136
01:35:52,328 --> 01:35:54,046
Unfair to organized womanhood.

1137
01:35:56,208 --> 01:35:58,768
Maybe if we extended this flange
down a little farther.

1138
01:35:58,928 --> 01:36:02,364
It won't do it, Joe. The movements
to the valve aren't fine enough.

1139
01:36:02,528 --> 01:36:06,283
You'll either get a slight trickle of
oxygen or a whole slug of it all at once.

1140
01:36:06,608 --> 01:36:09,600
You've got to have a smooth.
Fine. Hairline control.

1141
01:36:09,768 --> 01:36:11,998
How about a shampoo
and finger wave?

1142
01:36:12,168 --> 01:36:14,921
You know. I fly too.
But I'm not such a bore about it.

1143
01:36:15,088 --> 01:36:17,238
I can talk about other things
now and then.

1144
01:36:17,528 --> 01:36:19,963
We'll have to find somebody
to invent a new valve.

1145
01:36:20,128 --> 01:36:22,802
I'll try if you've got
another screwdriver.

1146
01:36:29,568 --> 01:36:31,525
Excuse me.

1147
01:36:31,928 --> 01:36:33,885
That shade won't be becoming to you.

1148
01:36:37,848 --> 01:36:40,078
Joe? Look.

1149
01:36:40,448 --> 01:36:42,564
A slide valve with a fine screw
on the stem.

1150
01:36:42,728 --> 01:36:44,765
Each turn opens it just a hair.

1151
01:36:44,928 --> 01:36:46,760
This is it.

1152
01:36:48,008 --> 01:36:50,761
Sure. That's got it. Look.

1153
01:36:50,928 --> 01:36:53,238
If we design something like this.
Have the outlet...

1154
01:36:53,408 --> 01:36:55,160
Will you gentlemen excuse us. Please?

1155
01:36:55,328 --> 01:36:58,878
Helen. Not so loud.
You might wake them up.

1156
01:37:01,688 --> 01:37:04,601
- And I said they'd be exciting.
- I'm disappointed in the Navy.

1157
01:37:04,768 --> 01:37:08,124
It's getting so a girl
can't compete with nuts and bolts.

1158
01:37:10,088 --> 01:37:12,602
Well. There's always the Marine Corps.

1159
01:37:12,768 --> 01:37:14,679
May I help you?

1160
01:37:16,008 --> 01:37:17,521
Yes.

1161
01:37:17,888 --> 01:37:20,448
This valve engages this gadget.
We're off to the races.

1162
01:37:20,608 --> 01:37:22,201
- Have we overlooked anything?
- No.

1163
01:37:25,368 --> 01:37:27,678
- Dr. Lee?
- Yeah.

1164
01:37:27,848 --> 01:37:31,159
Mrs. Fisher asked me
to give you this with a message.

1165
01:37:32,248 --> 01:37:33,568
Thanks.

1166
01:37:33,728 --> 01:37:36,242
"Hume Mechanics Magazine.“"

1167
01:37:36,528 --> 01:37:39,486
- What was the message?
- Sailors, you're an awful bore

1168
01:37:39,648 --> 01:37:41,446
Valves to you We've gone ashore

1169
01:37:41,608 --> 01:37:43,645
We don‘t like quarrels
We don‘t like scenes

1170
01:37:43,808 --> 01:37:45,799
The Navy's tau busy
We'll try the Marines

1171
01:38:12,968 --> 01:38:16,404
These pressure-cabin jobs are tricky.
Sure you understand all the controls?

1172
01:38:16,568 --> 01:38:18,957
- Pressure. Oxygen. Humidity. Temperature?
- Certainly.

1173
01:38:19,128 --> 01:38:23,884
Don't look toward the sun when you get up.
Its rays will blind you in that thin air.

1174
01:38:25,448 --> 01:38:27,439
Thanks. So long.

1175
01:38:36,448 --> 01:38:38,644
Why do we need oxygen masks
in a pressure cabin?

1176
01:38:38,808 --> 01:38:42,119
- We don't.
- What did we bring them along for?

1177
01:38:42,288 --> 01:38:44,564
Force of habit, I guess.

1178
01:39:41,048 --> 01:39:43,039
Just over 35.000 feet.

1179
01:39:45,328 --> 01:39:48,639
- How do you feel?
- I'm getting a little woozy.

1180
01:39:49,368 --> 01:39:51,803
Why can't we keep the pressure up?

1181
01:39:52,288 --> 01:39:54,484
Can't and still ventilate.

1182
01:39:56,448 --> 01:39:58,758
Supercharger is full on.

1183
01:40:00,168 --> 01:40:02,637
It's no good at this height.

1184
01:40:04,168 --> 01:40:06,523
What's our next move?

1185
01:40:08,848 --> 01:40:11,408
I don't know.
Maybe we better get out and walk.

1186
01:40:24,648 --> 01:40:25,968
Thirty-six thousand.

1187
01:41:00,608 --> 01:41:01,962
Picking up ice.

1188
01:41:34,928 --> 01:41:36,919
She's sweating.

1189
01:42:09,768 --> 01:42:11,202
Thirty-eight thousand.

1190
01:42:15,648 --> 01:42:17,685
I can't balance the temperature
and humidity.

1191
01:42:38,208 --> 01:42:40,768
She's sluggish on the controls.

1192
01:42:41,368 --> 01:42:43,041
Too much ice.

1193
01:42:59,648 --> 01:43:01,924
The de-icer's frozen.

1194
01:43:35,248 --> 01:43:36,568
Give me oxygen.

1195
01:44:58,528 --> 01:45:01,168
I guess I left you for a few minutes.

1196
01:45:01,368 --> 01:45:03,245
- Are you all right?
- Yeah. I'll take it.

1197
01:45:05,888 --> 01:45:09,358
Swing low. Sweet chariot.
I heard the horn that time.

1198
01:45:09,528 --> 01:45:12,361
- What horn?
- Gabriel's.

1199
01:45:52,328 --> 01:45:55,366
This is about the most attractive
piece of ground I ever stood on.

1200
01:45:55,528 --> 01:45:58,759
Yeah. We almost bought
6 feet of it apiece.

1201
01:46:00,808 --> 01:46:02,287
Cigarette?

1202
01:46:02,448 --> 01:46:04,519
Yeah. Thanks.

1203
01:46:07,128 --> 01:46:09,244
It's gonna be tough on Art.

1204
01:46:09,408 --> 01:46:12,560
Well. It wasn't exactly a picnic for us.

1205
01:46:14,848 --> 01:46:16,521
Thanks.

1206
01:46:22,808 --> 01:46:24,719
- How'd it go?
- Make a nice ice wagon. Art.

1207
01:46:24,888 --> 01:46:27,846
- That's about all.
- Took two of us to handle the controls.

1208
01:46:28,008 --> 01:46:30,807
We were busier than one-armed
paperhangers and twice as cold.

1209
01:46:30,968 --> 01:46:33,482
Cabin's too damp. It sweats
and gathers ice by the ton.

1210
01:46:33,648 --> 01:46:36,401
- Outside of that. It's perfect.
- For everything but flying.

1211
01:46:36,728 --> 01:46:39,083
Well. I guess that's that.

1212
01:46:39,248 --> 01:46:41,364
Here's where we're
starting all over again.

1213
01:46:41,528 --> 01:46:43,599
Send me a full report.

1214
01:46:43,768 --> 01:46:45,441
I'm glad you got it down all right.

1215
01:46:45,648 --> 01:46:48,447
Thanks. So are we.
Can I interest you in our pressure suit?

1216
01:46:49,048 --> 01:46:52,215
You're going to have less luck with that
than you had with my pressure cabin.

1217
01:46:53,488 --> 01:46:55,877
This puts the whole problem
right in your laps. Boys.

1218
01:46:56,048 --> 01:46:58,403
Fine. It's right where we want it.

1219
01:46:59,208 --> 01:47:03,247
- Is this where the oxygen line goes in? -
It fits here. There's a slide valve for it.

1220
01:47:03,408 --> 01:47:06,002
- Where does your microphone plug in?
- Here.

1221
01:47:06,168 --> 01:47:08,478
There's a communication system
built in the helmet.

1222
01:47:08,648 --> 01:47:10,082
- You can see it.
- Oh. I see.

1223
01:47:10,248 --> 01:47:13,127
Lieutenant, this is gonna look
just like a diver's helmet.

1224
01:47:13,288 --> 01:47:16,883
Well. We don't care if it looks like
a birdcage. Just so that it works.

1225
01:47:20,848 --> 01:47:23,442
Here's your oxygen line right here.

1226
01:47:36,768 --> 01:47:39,726
44.500.

1227
01:47:41,368 --> 01:47:43,928
44.700.

1228
01:47:44,808 --> 01:47:47,163
45.000. There it is.

1229
01:47:47,328 --> 01:47:50,047
That's enough.
It's time to come down.

1230
01:47:50,208 --> 01:47:53,326
Cut the motor.
Open the pressure valves wide.

1231
01:48:05,088 --> 01:48:07,557
- Get the valves in the back.
- Aye. Sir.

1232
01:48:08,168 --> 01:48:11,798
You'd be in horrible shape if a mosquito
got in there with you. Wouldn't you?

1233
01:48:13,968 --> 01:48:16,562
- How was it? - Great. Except
I feel like a fish in a bowl.

1234
01:48:16,728 --> 01:48:19,163
Fine. Lift it off easy.

1235
01:48:19,608 --> 01:48:21,406
- How did the valves work?
- Like a charm.

1236
01:48:21,568 --> 01:48:23,161
It was worth losing two dames over.

1237
01:48:23,328 --> 01:48:26,207
I'll fly this suit to 50.000 if
I have to climb hand over hand.

1238
01:48:26,368 --> 01:48:28,086
I better check on your ticker anyway.

1239
01:48:28,248 --> 01:48:29,807
- Breathe normally.
- I'm all right.

1240
01:48:29,968 --> 01:48:31,927
Considering its weight.
It's pretty comfortable.

1241
01:48:31,968 --> 01:48:32,968
I like to hear that.

1242
01:48:33,128 --> 01:48:35,199
Wouldn't like to play tennis
in it. Would you?

1243
01:48:35,368 --> 01:48:37,359
Let me butt in here.

1244
01:48:37,608 --> 01:48:40,122
Listen. Boys. I think you really
got something here.

1245
01:48:40,288 --> 01:48:43,007
I guess that's all. Come. I want
to take a Schneider on you.

1246
01:48:43,168 --> 01:48:45,967
- Why?
- Just to keep the practice.

1247
01:48:55,288 --> 01:48:57,723
Lance. You can't do it that way.

1248
01:48:57,888 --> 01:49:01,006
You can't hand a man a piece of paper
with that kind of news in it.

1249
01:49:01,168 --> 01:49:02,647
It's too cold-blooded.

1250
01:49:02,808 --> 01:49:06,597
If you got a better idea. I'm willing
to listen. You can't send it to him.

1251
01:49:06,768 --> 01:49:09,408
I suppose not. That would be worse.

1252
01:49:10,568 --> 01:49:12,605
Everything's all set.

1253
01:49:12,768 --> 01:49:14,918
The ship's raring to go.

1254
01:49:15,088 --> 01:49:17,398
Cigarette?
- No. Thanks.

1255
01:49:18,288 --> 01:49:19,642
- Lance?
- No. Thanks.

1256
01:49:20,648 --> 01:49:23,481
You boys gonna be out there
with a band to see me off?

1257
01:49:37,928 --> 01:49:39,487
Well. What's eating you guys?

1258
01:49:39,648 --> 01:49:41,605
One of your rabbits got the pip?

1259
01:49:42,128 --> 01:49:43,766
No.

1260
01:49:44,808 --> 01:49:47,527
I was just discussing it with Lance...

1261
01:49:48,608 --> 01:49:51,122
and it would be better
if you didn't make this hop.

1262
01:49:51,288 --> 01:49:52,926
No. This KING'S my baby.

1263
01:49:53,088 --> 01:49:55,477
What's the difference
who makes the test?

1264
01:49:55,648 --> 01:49:59,004
- You know the suit will work.
- You mean. We think it will work.

1265
01:49:59,408 --> 01:50:00,921
Come on. Level with me.

1266
01:50:01,088 --> 01:50:03,159
I smell some kind of a runaround.

1267
01:50:03,328 --> 01:50:05,968
No. There's no runaround. It's...

1268
01:50:07,128 --> 01:50:09,802
I wish I could think of some other way.
But I can't.

1269
01:50:09,968 --> 01:50:12,687
Your Schneider hit the chronic-fatigue
line this morning.

1270
01:50:12,848 --> 01:50:17,206
We checked it every way. Twenty times.
Backwards and forwards. No mistake.

1271
01:50:18,848 --> 01:50:20,646
You mean. I'm washed-up.

1272
01:50:20,808 --> 01:50:22,401
No. No. I wouldn't put it that way.

1273
01:50:22,568 --> 01:50:26,357
A man of your experience is always
gonna be valuable in the service.

1274
01:50:26,528 --> 01:50:28,644
So what if you have
to give up flying a while?

1275
01:50:28,808 --> 01:50:32,517
- You can keep running your squadron.
- Yeah.

1276
01:50:33,008 --> 01:50:37,161
I'll be a great example for those boys.
Parked in the office with my knitting.

1277
01:50:40,008 --> 01:50:42,807
I guess it had to happen
sooner or later.

1278
01:50:44,128 --> 01:50:48,087
It's tough to get yanked out of the ring
when the main event is about to start.

1279
01:50:48,248 --> 01:50:51,639
- After you've trained all your life.
- You've trained plenty of other guys.

1280
01:50:51,808 --> 01:50:54,926
If and when the main event does start.
They'll be in there pitching.

1281
01:50:55,088 --> 01:50:57,045
Sure. Sure they will.

1282
01:50:58,968 --> 01:51:00,641
Well...

1283
01:51:01,728 --> 01:51:03,958
it was a good show while it lasted.

1284
01:51:04,888 --> 01:51:07,402
I would like to have finished
this pressure-suit job...

1285
01:51:07,568 --> 01:51:09,878
before the rocking chair got me.

1286
01:51:11,648 --> 01:51:14,845
- Is that my diploma?
- Yeah.

1287
01:51:15,888 --> 01:51:18,118
I better take it just to make it official.

1288
01:51:19,648 --> 01:51:21,798
Say. Do you know...

1289
01:51:21,968 --> 01:51:25,404
some other man who can
do this test job for us?

1290
01:51:25,568 --> 01:51:27,878
Yeah. Yeah. I'll have
a good pilot for you.

1291
01:51:28,048 --> 01:51:29,561
Thanks.

1292
01:51:30,728 --> 01:51:32,321
Joe.

1293
01:51:33,128 --> 01:51:35,005
I wish there was something
I could say...

1294
01:51:35,368 --> 01:51:36,847
but there never is. Is there?

1295
01:51:52,048 --> 01:51:53,686
Commander Blake.

1296
01:51:53,848 --> 01:51:55,407
Yes?

1297
01:51:55,888 --> 01:51:58,562
I just wanted to thank you for
giving me another chance.

1298
01:51:58,728 --> 01:52:01,561
- Forget it.
- It's meant a lot to train under you. Sir.

1299
01:52:02,528 --> 01:52:05,486
Thanks. Just remember
one rule. Anthony:

1300
01:52:05,648 --> 01:52:07,878
As a pilot. Fight to be on top
and stay there.

1301
01:52:08,048 --> 01:52:11,757
- You can't lick them from below.
- I won't forget that. Sir.

1302
01:52:16,688 --> 01:52:18,042
- Is she ready?
- Yes, sir.

1303
01:52:18,208 --> 01:52:21,007
- Pull her out.
- All right, boys. Pull her out.

1304
01:52:33,888 --> 01:52:36,880
Just a minute. Sir.
There seems to be something wrong.

1305
01:52:42,408 --> 01:52:44,160
There. That's got it.

1306
01:53:07,328 --> 01:53:09,160
How'd he take it?

1307
01:53:09,328 --> 01:53:11,080
Not as hard as I thought he would.

1308
01:53:11,248 --> 01:53:13,603
That doesn't sound like Joe Blake.

1309
01:53:13,888 --> 01:53:16,687
No. Rotten job. Though.

1310
01:53:33,848 --> 01:53:37,478
- Who's in that plane that just took off?
Lieutenant Commander Blake, sir.

1311
01:54:13,168 --> 01:54:15,967
I want to contact Lieutenant
Commander Blake. He's in 6FOX4.

1312
01:54:16,168 --> 01:54:17,806
Very well.

1313
01:54:19,168 --> 01:54:22,604
San Diego. Calling Lieutenant
Commander Blake in 6FOX4.

1314
01:54:32,568 --> 01:54:36,038
San Diego. Calling Lieutenant
Commander Blake in 6FOX4.

1315
01:54:36,248 --> 01:54:38,808
This is Blake in 6FOX4. Go ahead.

1316
01:54:40,368 --> 01:54:43,406
Joe. This is Doug. What the devil
do you think you're doing?

1317
01:54:43,768 --> 01:54:47,124
I'd say I'm doing about 250
at 26.000 and going up.

1318
01:54:48,808 --> 01:54:51,243
Are you“? Don't try to take
that ship to its ceiling.

1319
01:54:51,448 --> 01:54:54,520
Why not? That was the whole idea.

1320
01:54:54,768 --> 01:54:57,487
I want to prove this.
Then you can turn me out to pasture.

1321
01:54:57,688 --> 01:55:00,362
Listen. You're in no shape to fly.
You've been grounded.

1322
01:55:00,568 --> 01:55:03,765
I can't hear you, pal.
The neighbors are playing the radio.

1323
01:55:06,328 --> 01:55:08,797
Joe. This is Lance. Don't be a fool.
Come on down.

1324
01:55:22,968 --> 01:55:25,926
Twenty-eight thousand.
This suit works like a charm.

1325
01:55:26,088 --> 01:55:27,920
We should open a tailor shop for angels.

1326
01:55:28,088 --> 01:55:30,125
Joe. That's high enough.
You've done the job.

1327
01:55:30,288 --> 01:55:31,608
Now head up for the stable.

1328
01:55:31,808 --> 01:55:34,322
I can't do a thing.
She's got the bit in her teeth.

1329
01:55:34,528 --> 01:55:35,848
Look...

1330
01:55:36,008 --> 01:55:38,443
the skipper's come in the room.
He's here with us.

1331
01:55:38,608 --> 01:55:39,928
He's ordering you to land.

1332
01:55:40,928 --> 01:55:44,637
Tell him he shouldn't be hanging around
the radio tower. It's undignified.

1333
01:55:52,728 --> 01:55:54,878
Thirty thousand.

1334
01:55:55,048 --> 01:55:56,447
Life begins at 40.

1335
01:55:56,648 --> 01:55:58,480
Listen to reason, you crazy idiot.

1336
01:55:58,768 --> 01:56:01,078
You guys are wasting my breath.
I'll see you later.

1337
01:56:02,768 --> 01:56:04,247
Joe.

1338
01:58:15,480 --> 01:58:17,551
Switched off.
Might as well argue with a wall.

1339
01:59:17,568 --> 01:59:19,366
That ship's out of control.

1340
02:00:25,064 --> 02:00:27,214
Sound the crash alarm.

1341
02:00:51,008 --> 02:00:53,568
“Heat oxygen line to prevent ice.

1342
02:00:53,728 --> 02:00:55,048
Suit perfect then.“

1343
02:01:54,888 --> 02:01:57,641
The sole purpose in forming
for this ceremony...

1344
02:01:57,808 --> 02:02:01,688
is to honor the men who. During the
year. Have done the most for the service.

1345
02:02:01,848 --> 02:02:05,728
So it's my privilege to make an award
of this trophy...

1346
02:02:05,888 --> 02:02:09,119
for the year's outstanding
achievement in aviation.

1347
02:02:09,568 --> 02:02:12,287
And so we honor two flight surgeons...

1348
02:02:12,448 --> 02:02:15,679
Lieutenant Commander Rogers
and Lieutenant Lee...

1349
02:02:15,848 --> 02:02:18,044
whose professional skill
has made possible...

1350
02:02:18,208 --> 02:02:21,917
the effective work
of our finest pilots and best planes.

1351
02:02:22,528 --> 02:02:26,044
These men have been instrumental in
solving some of the greatest problems...

1352
02:02:26,208 --> 02:02:27,528
in aviation medicine.

1353
02:02:27,728 --> 02:02:30,686
They've been more than faithful
to the flight surgeon's creed:

1354
02:02:30,848 --> 02:02:32,839
"Keep them in the air.“"

1355
02:02:33,368 --> 02:02:36,679
We also honor the memory of
Lieutenant Commander Joseph Blake...

1356
02:02:36,848 --> 02:02:40,204
who heroically sacrificed his life
in first testing the pressure suit.

1357
02:02:41,128 --> 02:02:43,483
His supreme sacrifice
was not made in vain.

1358
02:02:43,688 --> 02:02:46,362
It insured that the planes
and pilots of this nation...

1359
02:02:46,728 --> 02:02:52,724
can more safely fly. Fight and defend
their country in the stratosphere.

1360
02:02:53,488 --> 02:02:55,525
Lieutenant Lee.

1361
02:03:00,848 --> 02:03:03,727
I accept this. Sir. On behalf
of my friend and coworker...

1362
02:03:03,888 --> 02:03:05,447
Lieutenant Commander Blake.

1363
02:03:05,608 --> 02:03:07,997
A very gallant gentleman.

1364
02:03:32,848 --> 02:03:34,998
And salute.

1365
02:03:56,768 --> 02:03:58,884
Pilots. Man your planes.

1366
02:04:04,088 --> 02:04:05,761
Lieutenant?

1367
02:04:06,648 --> 02:04:08,958
I've been ordered to stay on duty
as an instructor.

1368
02:04:09,448 --> 02:04:11,883
Any time you need a guinea pig
for future research...

1369
02:04:12,048 --> 02:04:13,766
I'd like to carry on Blake's work.

1370
02:04:14,368 --> 02:04:16,279
That will be fine.
We'll let you know.

1371
02:04:16,448 --> 02:04:19,699
And. Sir. The pilots would like to have
you make this hop with us. If you wish.

1372
02:04:21,288 --> 02:04:22,622
Thanks. Thanks. I would like to.

1373
02:04:27,111 --> 02:04:28,111
.
